WEBVTT

00:12.603 --> 00:15.793
[SPEAKER_02]: We're live in Salford for a TV first.

00:15.813 --> 00:19.184
[SPEAKER_02]: It's Boris Johnson versus Jeremy Corbyn.

00:20.167 --> 00:21.752
[SPEAKER_02]: The ITV debate.

00:44.007 --> 00:44.508
[SPEAKER_02]: Good evening.

00:44.568 --> 00:51.075
[SPEAKER_02]: In just over three weeks, we'll be voting in what many think is the most important general election of our lifetimes.

00:51.155 --> 01:02.168
[SPEAKER_02]: Tonight, the Conservative Prime Minister Boris Johnson and the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, debate face-to-face, responding to questions from ITV viewers.

01:02.588 --> 01:05.712
[SPEAKER_02]: And you at home can take part too using the hashtag

01:05.692 --> 01:07.094
[SPEAKER_02]: ITV debate.

01:07.354 --> 01:22.013
[SPEAKER_02]: Later tonight at 10 o'clock, you'll be able to see other leaders on ITV when Lib Dem Joe Swinson, the SNP's Nicola Sturgeon, the Brexit Party's Nigel Farage and Green Party co-leader Sian Berry will be interviewed live by Nina Hussain.

01:22.354 --> 01:26.559
[SPEAKER_02]: But now it's time for Boris Johnson versus Jeremy Corbyn.

01:26.579 --> 01:31.886
[SPEAKER_02]: Before we take our first question tonight, they'll each now make an opening statement.

01:32.026 --> 01:33.488
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, it's over to you.

01:34.312 --> 01:37.987
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Julie, and to everyone watching this debate tonight.

01:38.730 --> 01:42.988
[SPEAKER_17]: This election gives you a real choice about your future.

01:43.762 --> 01:47.085
[SPEAKER_17]: the future of your community and of our country.

01:47.786 --> 01:50.729
[SPEAKER_17]: Labour is offering real change and real hope.

01:51.550 --> 01:56.755
[SPEAKER_17]: We will build a fairer Britain that cares for all, where wealth and power are shared.

01:57.455 --> 01:59.257
[SPEAKER_17]: The Conservative government is failing.

01:59.718 --> 02:06.184
[SPEAKER_17]: It's failed on the economy, on the climate crisis, the National Health Service and on Brexit.

02:06.204 --> 02:13.431
[SPEAKER_17]: We will get Brexit sorted by giving you, the people, the final say and implement whatever you decide.

02:14.373 --> 02:22.323
[SPEAKER_17]: Too many families are without a proper home, struggling to make ends meet, while tax cuts are handed to the super-rich.

02:22.984 --> 02:27.349
[SPEAKER_17]: We can do better than this, with a Labour government on your side.

02:27.790 --> 02:34.238
[SPEAKER_17]: A Labour government for the many, not just the few.

02:42.622 --> 02:43.604
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Julian.

02:43.684 --> 02:44.545
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr Corbyn.

02:44.565 --> 02:47.711
[SPEAKER_04]: There's only one reason why we're having this election.

02:47.731 --> 02:52.539
[SPEAKER_04]: That is that we have a deadlocked parliament that will not deliver Brexit.

02:52.559 --> 03:01.755
[SPEAKER_04]: And whether you voted for leave or remain, people want to get Brexit done and to unleash the potential of this entire country.

03:02.156 --> 03:04.680
[SPEAKER_04]: And we Conservatives can.

03:04.660 --> 03:15.834
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if you vote for us, we have a deal that is ready to go, approved by every one of the 635 Conservative candidates standing at this election.

03:16.174 --> 03:23.343
[SPEAKER_04]: And as soon as we can get that deal through Parliament, as we can in the next few weeks, we can get on with the people's priorities.

03:23.603 --> 03:25.285
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's the choice.

03:25.265 --> 03:35.616
[SPEAKER_04]: dither and delay, deadlock and division under a Corbyn-Sturgeon coalition with two referendums, another one on the EU and then another one on Scotland.

03:35.976 --> 03:49.250
[SPEAKER_04]: Or we can end this national misery, break the deadlock, get Brexit done, and make 2020 a year of prosperity and growth where we invest in our NHS and deal with the cost of living.

03:49.530 --> 03:52.573
[SPEAKER_04]: Together, let's take this country forwards.

03:53.054 --> 03:54.175
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr Johnson.

03:59.352 --> 04:03.136
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we invited viewers from right across the country to submit questions.

04:03.196 --> 04:06.820
[SPEAKER_02]: We've selected the questioners, and they are in the studio with us this evening.

04:06.840 --> 04:09.202
[SPEAKER_02]: The two leaders don't know what they'll be asked.

04:09.382 --> 04:12.706
[SPEAKER_02]: Also here, the people who will listen to tonight's debate.

04:12.786 --> 04:19.853
[SPEAKER_02]: Some have voted Conservative and some Labour in the past, and some have voted for other parties across the UK.

04:19.913 --> 04:24.077
[SPEAKER_02]: And our first question tonight comes from Cath Sherlock from Bradford.

04:25.289 --> 04:31.645
[SPEAKER_14]: Both of you have promised that Brexit will be resolved in the next few months, but you're really telling us the truth.

04:32.406 --> 04:34.331
[SPEAKER_14]: There have been so many broken promises.

04:34.993 --> 04:39.163
[SPEAKER_14]: Can you reassure me that we will not be talking about this forever?

04:40.342 --> 04:42.486
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, Kath.

04:42.506 --> 04:45.311
[SPEAKER_02]: So a question about the timetable for Brexit.

04:45.792 --> 04:48.316
[SPEAKER_02]: To respond first, Mr Johnson.

04:49.017 --> 04:50.340
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you very much, Kath.

04:50.360 --> 04:57.272
[SPEAKER_04]: And yes, we certainly will come out on January the 31st, because we have a deal that, as I say, is oven ready.

04:57.312 --> 04:58.975
[SPEAKER_04]: It's ready to go.

04:58.955 --> 05:06.689
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's approved, as I say, not just by our friends and partners in the EU, but by every one of the 635 Conservative candidates.

05:06.770 --> 05:10.577
[SPEAKER_04]: And it delivers everything that we wanted from Brexit.

05:10.717 --> 05:14.224
[SPEAKER_04]: Our whole country comes out entire and perfect.

05:14.244 --> 05:16.628
[SPEAKER_04]: England, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland together.

05:17.069 --> 05:20.355
[SPEAKER_04]: And there is a sharp distinction between what we are proposing

05:20.335 --> 05:23.399
[SPEAKER_04]: getting Brexit done, unleashing the potential of this country.

05:23.800 --> 05:36.498
[SPEAKER_04]: And next year, dither and delay with another referendum on the EU when Jeremy Corbyn, Mr Corbyn, cannot tell us which side he would campaign on in that referendum.

05:36.518 --> 05:37.339
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you, Mr Johnson.

05:37.359 --> 05:41.044
[SPEAKER_02]: Your time's up for your first response, your first response to Kath's question.

05:41.024 --> 05:43.648
[SPEAKER_17]: Our priority is obviously to get it sorted.

05:44.049 --> 06:02.279
[SPEAKER_17]: We will, within three months, negotiate a credible leave option with the European Union and within six months put that to a referendum of the British people to decide between that option of leaving whilst protecting jobs and trade and the Good Friday Agreement with Europe or remaining as full members of the European Union.

06:02.579 --> 06:04.703
[SPEAKER_17]: That will be the choice put before the British people.

06:05.084 --> 06:05.985
[SPEAKER_17]: The idea

06:05.965 --> 06:12.455
[SPEAKER_17]: that the Prime Minister Boris Johnson's deal can be dealt with and finished by the end of January is such nonsense.

06:12.716 --> 06:23.332
[SPEAKER_17]: What he's proposing is a trade deal with the United States that would take at least seven years to negotiate, whilst at the same time saying he would negotiate a special trade deal with the European Union.

06:23.613 --> 06:25.756
[SPEAKER_17]: The two things are actually incompatible.

06:25.976 --> 06:27.619
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr Corbyn.

06:34.231 --> 06:47.289
[SPEAKER_02]: So to open the debate, Mr Johnson said that he claims he has a deal that is ready to go, that you would have to negotiate a new deal after three years since we voted to lead the European Union.

06:47.429 --> 06:49.455
[SPEAKER_02]: On that point, how would you respond?

06:49.435 --> 07:04.270
[SPEAKER_17]: Well the Prime Minister Boris Johnson voted twice against Theresa May's deal, one time for it, then proposed his own deal which narrowly got through the House of Commons with the support of the DUP, which is actually even worse than Theresa May's deal.

07:04.451 --> 07:05.453
[SPEAKER_17]: He cannot

07:05.433 --> 07:08.379
[SPEAKER_17]: protect jobs in this country on that basis.

07:08.820 --> 07:16.177
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think it is time that we actually recognise we have to maintain a firm and good trading relationship with Europe.

07:16.197 --> 07:21.889
[SPEAKER_17]: Otherwise, more jobs will be lost all over the country as they've already been lost because of the uncertainty.

07:21.869 --> 07:33.103
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we have a great deal that is supported, as Mr Corbyn says, not just by many members of his own party, but by the entire Conservative Party now.

07:33.163 --> 07:36.727
[SPEAKER_04]: And 635 Conservative candidates have backed it.

07:37.288 --> 07:39.450
[SPEAKER_04]: And what is the alternative?

07:39.951 --> 07:45.177
[SPEAKER_04]: It's under Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party to consecrate next year

07:45.157 --> 07:54.889
[SPEAKER_04]: to a three-month extension in which Mr Corbyn proposes to negotiate a new treaty, and then to put that to the people in a referendum.

07:55.089 --> 08:00.756
[SPEAKER_04]: But we don't know, and I've asked this before, we don't know on which side Mr Corbyn would campaign.

08:01.096 --> 08:03.499
[SPEAKER_04]: Is he going to campaign for leave or remain?

08:03.559 --> 08:05.541
[SPEAKER_02]: Can we ask Mr Corbyn to respond to that?

08:05.561 --> 08:06.963
[SPEAKER_17]: Very clearly, we will.

08:08.425 --> 08:08.785
[SPEAKER_17]: We will negotiate.

08:10.790 --> 08:17.362
[SPEAKER_17]: We will negotiate an agreement and we will put that alongside remain in a referendum.

08:17.802 --> 08:20.087
[SPEAKER_17]: And our government will abide by that result.

08:20.267 --> 08:22.531
[SPEAKER_17]: I will carry out the result of that referendum.

08:22.551 --> 08:28.782
[SPEAKER_17]: There will be a genuine choice put before the people of Britain to make their decision and we will carry it out.

08:34.077 --> 08:39.422
[SPEAKER_04]: At this election, what we're asking is for a mandate to govern.

08:39.442 --> 08:46.368
[SPEAKER_04]: And Mr Corbyn is asking the people for a mandate to conduct a new negotiation next year when we don't need one, because we've already got a deal.

08:46.629 --> 08:53.195
[SPEAKER_04]: I think what people need to understand is whether he believes in the deal that he is proposing to do.

08:53.795 --> 08:56.177
[SPEAKER_04]: Does he actually want to do this deal?

08:56.318 --> 09:02.143
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if he doesn't believe in it, or if, absurdly, he was then going to campaign against it,

09:02.123 --> 09:03.444
[SPEAKER_04]: in the forthcoming referendum.

09:03.504 --> 09:05.266
[SPEAKER_04]: Perhaps you'd like to put the question directly to Mr Corbyn.

09:05.286 --> 09:07.429
[SPEAKER_04]: What is the point of Brussels offering him?

09:07.449 --> 09:08.230
[SPEAKER_04]: Put the question to Mr Corbyn.

09:08.290 --> 09:13.195
[SPEAKER_04]: And I wonder whether Mr Corbyn can now tell us, are you going to campaign for leave or remain?

09:13.215 --> 09:22.505
[SPEAKER_17]: I want to bring people together, therefore there will be a referendum in which that decision will be made by the British people and our government will abide by that decision.

09:22.805 --> 09:25.228
[SPEAKER_17]: When you say you'll get it done,

09:25.478 --> 09:32.426
[SPEAKER_17]: Really, Mr. Johnson, you are going to embark on probably seven years of negotiations with the United States on a trade deal.

09:32.847 --> 09:40.516
[SPEAKER_17]: You've already indicated that you will allow our National Health Service to be put at risk by a trade deal with the United States.

09:41.036 --> 09:46.743
[SPEAKER_17]: You've already indicated that you would do a Canada-style agreement, which took at least seven years to negotiate.

09:47.063 --> 09:51.148
[SPEAKER_17]: So you're not going to get it done in a few months, and you know that perfectly well.

09:56.022 --> 10:08.457
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm noting here, of course, that we haven't heard whether you would campaign for Remain or leave in that situation, but it is important that we put the point that you have just made directly to Mr Johnson about this timetable.

10:08.757 --> 10:10.219
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's have a look at the timetable.

10:10.279 --> 10:16.166
[SPEAKER_02]: You reckon that you can get your divorce deal done and a trade deal done by December 2020.

10:16.467 --> 10:20.351
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you stick on a pledge on that deadline of December 2020?

10:20.792 --> 10:21.793
[SPEAKER_02]: Have you dug yourself a new

10:21.773 --> 10:22.934
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, absolutely.

10:22.974 --> 10:29.941
[SPEAKER_04]: Because people said, don't forget, people said that we couldn't do a new deal in three months.

10:30.361 --> 10:33.224
[SPEAKER_04]: People said that they would never open up the treaty.

10:33.244 --> 10:34.605
[SPEAKER_04]: They said it was impossible to do.

10:34.946 --> 10:36.207
[SPEAKER_04]: Actually, we succeeded.

10:36.227 --> 10:40.791
[SPEAKER_04]: And we have a great new deal that, as I say, is oven ready, ready to go.

10:41.031 --> 10:44.314
[SPEAKER_04]: And I hear what Jeremy Corbyn has to say about it.

10:44.354 --> 10:46.617
[SPEAKER_02]: Would you mint a new coin for December 2020?

10:47.037 --> 10:50.160
[SPEAKER_04]: I hear what people say about it.

10:50.748 --> 11:04.064
[SPEAKER_04]: No, we have ample time to do a fantastic free trade deal with our friends and partners in the EU, because we're already in a state of perfect alignment, both for tariffs and for quotas.

11:04.244 --> 11:05.846
[SPEAKER_04]: And we still have not heard, Julie.

11:05.906 --> 11:06.487
[SPEAKER_04]: You will notice.

11:06.928 --> 11:08.049
[SPEAKER_04]: I've answered your questions.

11:08.069 --> 11:10.792
[SPEAKER_04]: But there is a glaring lacuna still in this debate.

11:10.953 --> 11:12.975
[SPEAKER_04]: We still don't know.

11:12.955 --> 11:17.180
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry to say, we still don't know.

11:17.220 --> 11:18.742
[SPEAKER_04]: There is a vast emanation.

11:19.203 --> 11:19.704
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

11:19.884 --> 11:22.407
[SPEAKER_04]: Allow Mr. Corbyn to respond to the question from Mr. Johnson.

11:22.427 --> 11:25.992
[SPEAKER_04]: Is Jeremy Corbyn going to campaign for the deal he proposes to do?

11:26.392 --> 11:31.298
[SPEAKER_04]: Or is he going to invite his Labour colleagues to destroy the contraption that he's created?

11:31.318 --> 11:33.281
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, let's allow Mr. Corbyn to respond to that.

11:33.381 --> 11:33.922
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

11:33.942 --> 11:37.326
[SPEAKER_17]: That's what I've said, and it's very clear, very clear.

11:37.306 --> 11:43.133
[SPEAKER_17]: Three months to negotiate, six months for a referendum, and that will bring that process to an end.

11:43.413 --> 11:59.391
[SPEAKER_17]: What we know of the government's proposals, what we know of what Mr. Johnson has done is a series of secret meetings with the United States in which they were proposing to open up our NHS markets, as they call them, to American companies.

11:59.791 --> 12:04.697
[SPEAKER_17]: Freedom of Information Act request was made in order to find out what happened at these meetings.

12:04.677 --> 12:05.959
[SPEAKER_17]: That's what happened at these meetings.

12:06.520 --> 12:09.544
[SPEAKER_17]: Every single line of this document redacted out.

12:10.025 --> 12:15.093
[SPEAKER_17]: A document here, a document here of US-UK negotiations.

12:15.554 --> 12:18.178
[SPEAKER_17]: Summary of specific negotiating objectives.

12:18.198 --> 12:22.645
[SPEAKER_17]: Full market access for US products to our National Health Service.

12:22.845 --> 12:28.153
[SPEAKER_17]: You're going to sell our National Health Service out to the United States and Big Pharma.

12:28.133 --> 12:32.402
[SPEAKER_04]: This is an absolute invention.

12:32.843 --> 12:34.306
[SPEAKER_04]: It is completely untrue.

12:34.606 --> 12:44.287
[SPEAKER_04]: There are no circumstances, whatever, in which this government or any conservative government will put the NHS on the table in any trade negotiation.

12:44.447 --> 12:46.952
[SPEAKER_04]: Our NHS will never be for sale.

12:46.932 --> 12:48.675
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm amazed how often this comes up.

12:48.695 --> 13:02.019
[SPEAKER_04]: The only reason that it comes up is because Mr. Corbyn is trying to conceal the void at the heart of his Brexit policy and refusing to answer the question of which side, which side he would take.

13:02.039 --> 13:05.325
[SPEAKER_04]: Because the public still, the public have a right, the public have a right to know.

13:05.345 --> 13:05.966
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay, thank you Mr. Corbyn.

13:06.006 --> 13:07.669
[SPEAKER_20]: Just very, just very briefly.

13:07.870 --> 13:09.052
[SPEAKER_17]: I've made the position clear.

13:09.332 --> 13:10.915
[SPEAKER_17]: We will have a referendum.

13:10.895 --> 13:15.120
[SPEAKER_17]: We will have negotiations, and we will abide by that result.

13:15.360 --> 13:18.004
[SPEAKER_17]: It's the British people who will make that decision.

13:18.104 --> 13:19.285
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, we've heard that.

13:19.385 --> 13:20.166
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Corbyn.

13:20.186 --> 13:20.807
[SPEAKER_17]: We've heard that.

13:20.847 --> 13:35.485
[SPEAKER_17]: I do think, though, that since the Prime Minister has claimed the NHS is not under threat, why then did his government agree with the US that there should be, in the terms of negotiations, full market access for United States medical companies

13:35.465 --> 13:37.647
[SPEAKER_17]: into our national health service.

13:37.667 --> 13:40.870
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, we're going to talk about the NHS a little further a little later.

13:41.391 --> 13:44.974
[SPEAKER_02]: And we're now going to go to our next questioner.

13:45.014 --> 13:53.422
[SPEAKER_02]: Staying with the issue of Brexit, John Firth wants to ask about the possible threat to the Union, which could mean the breakup of the United Kingdom.

13:53.662 --> 13:53.802
[SPEAKER_02]: John.

13:54.223 --> 13:56.845
[SPEAKER_04]: Is the Union worth sacrificing for Brexit?

13:58.147 --> 13:59.888
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed for that.

14:00.048 --> 14:03.852
[SPEAKER_02]: Is the Union worth sacrificing for Brexit, Mr Corbyn?

14:04.726 --> 14:31.442
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I hope the union is not going to be broken up or sacrificed in this way, but the agreements that the Prime Minister negotiated or he's put, not negotiated, he's put towards the Parliament was about creating a border between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland, creating a different customs arrangement for Northern Ireland with the rest of Ireland, having promised to the Democratic Unionist Party he would never do that.

14:31.422 --> 14:33.224
[SPEAKER_17]: Clearly, there is an issue there.

14:33.524 --> 14:37.409
[SPEAKER_17]: Clearly, there are issues all around about this deal that he's proposed.

14:37.429 --> 14:54.949
[SPEAKER_17]: And I do think that this deal is damaging to this country, damaging to the rights we have at work and consumer protection and environmental protection in this country, and very damaging to manufacturing industry jobs all over Britain, some of which have already gone because of uncertainty over Brexit.

14:54.929 --> 14:56.832
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, Mr Corbyn, Mr Johnson.

14:56.852 --> 15:02.860
[SPEAKER_04]: We have a deal that keeps the whole of the UK together as we come out of the EU.

15:02.940 --> 15:15.638
[SPEAKER_04]: And of course, Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party, be in no doubt about it, in order to secure power and the keys to number 10, are going to do a deal, and they probably already have done a deal, with Nicola Sturgeon and the SNP.

15:15.618 --> 15:18.000
[SPEAKER_04]: to form a Corbyn-Sturgeon coalition.

15:18.180 --> 15:28.069
[SPEAKER_04]: And the price of that deal, the price of Nicola Sturgeon's support, let's be in no doubt, she's made it absolutely clear, would be a second referendum on the union with Scotland.

15:28.309 --> 15:30.551
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't think we need another referendum on the union with Scotland.

15:30.831 --> 15:31.332
[SPEAKER_04]: I've ruled it out.

15:31.532 --> 15:32.653
[SPEAKER_04]: We had one in 2014.

15:32.693 --> 15:39.739
[SPEAKER_04]: The people of Scotland voted very substantially to stay in the most successful political partnership of the last 300 years.

15:39.919 --> 15:43.262
[SPEAKER_04]: Why put this country, this great country, through another referendum on Scotland?

15:43.422 --> 15:45.304
[SPEAKER_04]: And why have a second referendum?

15:45.284 --> 15:47.789
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you very much indeed.

15:47.930 --> 15:48.371
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

15:48.391 --> 15:51.698
[SPEAKER_02]: That's time up on your first response to that.

15:51.738 --> 15:52.760
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed.

15:52.780 --> 15:57.510
[SPEAKER_02]: So just as a quick, you know, set something down in front of us, gentlemen.

15:57.551 --> 16:00.878
[SPEAKER_02]: For clarity, is the union more important than Brexit?

16:00.938 --> 16:01.960
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes or no?

16:03.037 --> 16:06.847
[SPEAKER_17]: I think I ought to be able to reply to this nonsense.

16:06.867 --> 16:07.729
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you be able to reply?

16:07.790 --> 16:09.213
[SPEAKER_17]: I'd just like to have it.

16:09.334 --> 16:12.643
[SPEAKER_17]: There's not going to be a coalition between Labour and the SNP.

16:12.803 --> 16:15.390
[SPEAKER_17]: There's not going to be a coalition between Labour and anybody else.

16:15.570 --> 16:19.240
[SPEAKER_17]: There are no deals that have been done and there will be no deals that are done.

16:21.515 --> 16:25.924
[SPEAKER_02]: For charity, is the union more important than Brexit, Mr Corbyn?

16:26.024 --> 16:38.330
[SPEAKER_17]: Our country is obviously very, very important and we have to bring this business to a close and that's why we're proposing a trade deal with Europe or staying in, one or the other, as a way of bringing this issue to a close.

16:38.350 --> 16:39.051
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr Johnson.

16:39.031 --> 16:46.519
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Bliski, the union is, of course, the most important thing, just to answer the question straight.

16:46.539 --> 16:47.740
[SPEAKER_04]: The union, and it's a fantastic thing.

16:48.521 --> 16:51.564
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm proud to be not only prime minister, but also minister for the union.

16:51.584 --> 17:02.155
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Now, let's be clear that Jeremy Corbyn has said that he's open to a second referendum on Scotland early in the lifetime of the next parliament if he's head of the government.

17:02.455 --> 17:06.439
[SPEAKER_04]: And Nicola Sturgeon has made it absolutely clear that the price of her support

17:06.419 --> 17:09.463
[SPEAKER_04]: will be a referendum on Scotland in 2020.

17:10.044 --> 17:16.233
[SPEAKER_04]: So you're going to have a year of two referendums, one on Scotland and one... OK, let's allow Mr Corbyn to respond.

17:16.253 --> 17:17.795
[SPEAKER_02]: One on Scotland and one on the EU.

17:17.815 --> 17:19.117
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, if you do have to...

17:19.137 --> 17:19.978
[SPEAKER_02]: The opposite's the case, actually.

17:20.038 --> 17:28.951
[SPEAKER_02]: If you do have to get to a point where you have to make a deal with the SNP, Nicola Sturgeon has already said, don't pick up the phone unless you can guarantee a second independence referendum.

17:29.311 --> 17:32.055
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you rule it out before the end of the first year?

17:32.035 --> 17:45.319
[SPEAKER_17]: I've said there would be no deal with the SNP, there would be no support for a Scottish referendum in the early years of the next Labour government because I want to invest in Scotland and give Scotland the £70 billion it needs in capital investment.

17:45.439 --> 17:53.453
[SPEAKER_17]: If the SNP leadership choose to put the Conservative government back in office with its austerity programme, that's their choice.

17:54.023 --> 18:00.070
[SPEAKER_04]: I listened very carefully, as I always do, to Mr Corbyn.

18:00.110 --> 18:03.254
[SPEAKER_04]: I didn't hear him say he was going to rule out a referendum on Scotland.

18:03.274 --> 18:03.755
[SPEAKER_04]: Did you?

18:03.775 --> 18:06.358
[SPEAKER_04]: We're ruling out a referendum.

18:06.698 --> 18:14.888
[SPEAKER_04]: It's perfectly clear that the price of Nicola Sturgeon's support for the chaotic coalition that he would comprise is a second referendum.

18:14.908 --> 18:15.229
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you.

18:15.249 --> 18:16.210
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's allow him to respond.

18:16.230 --> 18:16.871
[SPEAKER_04]: Can you rule it out?

18:16.891 --> 18:19.474
[SPEAKER_17]: We've witnessed nine years of chaotic coalitions already.

18:23.453 --> 18:28.000
[SPEAKER_02]: OK. Can I turn, please, to the issue of Northern Ireland?

18:28.080 --> 18:38.235
[SPEAKER_02]: In your hustings for your leadership race, Mr Johnson, you said, under no circumstances, whatever happens, will I allow the EU or anyone else to create any division down the Irish Sea?

18:38.455 --> 18:42.782
[SPEAKER_02]: You spoke at another conference a year ago, saying that that would damage the fabric of the union.

18:43.082 --> 18:43.723
[SPEAKER_02]: And now?

18:43.703 --> 18:46.288
[SPEAKER_02]: Here we have your deal that you've presented to Parliament.

18:46.388 --> 18:46.909
[SPEAKER_04]: Absolutely.

18:47.029 --> 18:56.807
[SPEAKER_04]: And that deal means that the whole of the UK can come out and do free trade deals around the world and do a great deal with our EU friends and partners, Northern Ireland included.

18:56.987 --> 18:58.911
[SPEAKER_04]: What the people of Northern Ireland don't know.

18:58.891 --> 19:00.755
[SPEAKER_02]: A trade deal down the Irish Sea?

19:00.855 --> 19:02.558
[SPEAKER_02]: A trade border down the Irish Sea?

19:02.578 --> 19:03.219
[SPEAKER_04]: Not at all.

19:03.259 --> 19:06.646
[SPEAKER_04]: Northern Ireland is part of the customs territory of the UK.

19:06.726 --> 19:08.409
[SPEAKER_04]: It's there in black and white.

19:08.429 --> 19:21.895
[SPEAKER_04]: And what the people of Northern Ireland do not know, and part of our tariff schedules and everything else, what the people of Northern Ireland do not know, and nor do the people of Ireland, is what kind of deal Jeremy Corbyn proposes to do.

19:21.875 --> 19:29.529
[SPEAKER_04]: And he's got 100 of his MPs, and we still don't know, by the way, what he proposes to do, nor whether he's in favour of it or against it.

19:29.950 --> 19:36.542
[SPEAKER_04]: We have 100 of his MPs who have already said that they would vote against it.

19:36.883 --> 19:39.147
[SPEAKER_04]: Most of the shadow cabinet are against the deal.

19:39.167 --> 19:39.868
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

19:39.888 --> 19:40.449
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Corbyn.

19:40.509 --> 19:41.651
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

19:41.712 --> 19:42.533
[SPEAKER_20]: A quick response.

19:42.513 --> 19:48.205
[SPEAKER_17]: The problem with what Mr Johnson just said is that he said exactly the opposite when he spoke to a DUP conference.

19:48.225 --> 19:51.191
[SPEAKER_17]: You said there would be no border down the Irish Sea.

19:51.271 --> 19:51.792
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, there is!

19:52.273 --> 19:52.934
[SPEAKER_04]: On the contrary.

19:53.375 --> 19:54.377
[SPEAKER_04]: On the contrary.

19:54.397 --> 19:58.345
[SPEAKER_04]: The whole of the UK comes out entire and perfect as I have.

19:58.325 --> 20:13.735
[SPEAKER_04]: said, we do free trade deals together, we take back control together, we have our own immigration system for instance, we can take back control of our borders and one of the many mysteries about Mr Corbyn's deal is would he take back control

20:13.715 --> 20:15.798
[SPEAKER_04]: of immigration, which people voted for.

20:15.818 --> 20:17.281
[SPEAKER_02]: We are going to stay on the issue of Brexit.

20:17.301 --> 20:19.404
[SPEAKER_04]: We are going to have an Australian-style points-based system.

20:19.424 --> 20:20.165
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

20:20.185 --> 20:21.507
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to stay on the issue of Brexit.

20:21.547 --> 20:22.328
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

20:22.348 --> 20:24.452
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to stay on this issue of Brexit.

20:24.532 --> 20:29.580
[SPEAKER_02]: And underlying this whole issue, of course, is the question of trust and leadership.

20:29.620 --> 20:31.923
[SPEAKER_02]: We have had hundreds of questions on this.

20:32.043 --> 20:34.587
[SPEAKER_02]: And with that in mind, it's over to Fahad Sayyed.

20:35.949 --> 20:41.578
[SPEAKER_16]: This whole nation will have watched you both throughout this campaign in utter despair.

20:41.744 --> 20:45.931
[SPEAKER_16]: At the heart of all of this is one very simple question.

20:45.951 --> 20:46.892
[SPEAKER_16]: How can we trust you?

20:54.324 --> 21:02.336
[SPEAKER_16]: Under your leadership the debate has become toxic and degraded with an appalling level of lies and childish abuse.

21:03.037 --> 21:04.039
[SPEAKER_16]: How can this nation

21:05.521 --> 21:17.279
[SPEAKER_16]: How can this nation trust you to have the personal integrity and individual strength of character to look after our country's interest, rescue us from this mess, and bring us back together?

21:18.441 --> 21:23.428
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed.

21:23.448 --> 21:25.251
[SPEAKER_04]: Is it fired?

21:25.737 --> 21:26.959
[SPEAKER_04]: I think fine.

21:26.979 --> 21:30.484
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you very much for a very important question.

21:30.544 --> 21:37.835
[SPEAKER_04]: And look, on the issue of trust, I think that trust in politics and in Parliament has been corroded.

21:38.215 --> 21:52.116
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the most fundamental reason for that is because Parliament asked the people to vote on membership of the EU, and then Parliament has repeatedly refused to honour that promise, to respect the views of the people.

21:52.096 --> 21:58.303
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm afraid this, Jeremy Corbyn, Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party are now blocking Brexit.

21:58.343 --> 22:05.731
[SPEAKER_04]: The way I think, which is absolutely true, the way to restore trust in politics is to get Brexit done and move forward.

22:05.831 --> 22:08.254
[SPEAKER_04]: We have a great deal that enables us to do it.

22:08.794 --> 22:16.142
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm unclear as to why it's necessary to spend another year in a debate about Brexit, which is, as Farhan says, corrosive advice.

22:16.162 --> 22:16.723
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much.

22:16.763 --> 22:18.745
[SPEAKER_02]: Time is up, Mr Corbyn, your first response.

22:19.687 --> 22:22.934
[SPEAKER_17]: Trust is something that has to be earned.

22:23.696 --> 22:29.650
[SPEAKER_17]: And as a public representative, you have to listen to the people that elected you in the first place.

22:30.111 --> 22:33.479
[SPEAKER_17]: And you have to listen to people all over the country in all walks of life.

22:33.719 --> 22:37.628
[SPEAKER_17]: I spend a great deal of time traveling around the country listening to people.

22:37.996 --> 22:42.963
[SPEAKER_17]: be they chief executives, workers, people sweeping the street, or the homeless.

22:43.364 --> 22:45.908
[SPEAKER_17]: Everybody you meet knows something you don't know.

22:45.968 --> 22:57.385
[SPEAKER_17]: Leadership is about listening to people, trying to put their ideas into practice, and finally come to a decision in which you can take your country and our society forward.

22:57.405 --> 23:05.657
[SPEAKER_17]: My style of leadership is actually to listen to people and try and bring consensus together in my own party and, obviously, within Parliament because,

23:05.637 --> 23:09.121
[SPEAKER_17]: The issues we face of division in our society do have to be conquered.

23:09.321 --> 23:19.073
[SPEAKER_17]: They're not going to be conquered by diktat, but only by listening and taking us forward that way.

23:19.093 --> 23:19.494
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much.

23:19.514 --> 23:23.619
[SPEAKER_02]: Farhad put his finger right on something very specific in this question.

23:23.699 --> 23:29.446
[SPEAKER_02]: How can the nation trust you to have the personal integrity and the individual strength of character?

23:29.826 --> 23:31.408
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, how would you respond to that?

23:31.844 --> 23:41.852
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I think we have to represent people, take decisions and be honest with people about why you're taking a decision that you are and how to bring people together.

23:42.113 --> 23:55.084
[SPEAKER_17]: My whole strategy on Brexit has been to recognise whether you voted remain and live in a private rented accommodation and in poor and in London, voted leave and you live in the North and are in the same situation, your issues are the same.

23:55.364 --> 23:59.287
[SPEAKER_17]: The problems of poverty, inequality and division within our society.

23:59.307 --> 24:01.429
[SPEAKER_17]: Bring people together, don't divide them.

24:03.670 --> 24:11.601
[SPEAKER_04]: I would just say to Farhan, look at what I have said I'm going to do as a politician and look what I've delivered.

24:11.621 --> 24:22.797
[SPEAKER_04]: Whether it was as Mayor of London or now as Prime Minister, I said that we would put 20,000 more police officers on the streets of our city, of our country, and we are recruiting them now.

24:23.178 --> 24:26.643
[SPEAKER_04]: I said we'd upgrade 20 hospitals and have 40 new hospitals.

24:26.863 --> 24:28.986
[SPEAKER_04]: That programme is going ahead.

24:28.966 --> 24:32.270
[SPEAKER_04]: We are uplifting funding for education across the country.

24:32.450 --> 24:36.555
[SPEAKER_04]: We're lifting up the living wage by its biggest ever expansion.

24:36.675 --> 24:40.859
[SPEAKER_04]: And I said we would deliver Brexit, and we will deliver Brexit.

24:40.879 --> 24:41.240
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

24:41.260 --> 24:44.684
[SPEAKER_04]: But we can only do it if we clear this parliamentary blockage.

24:44.704 --> 24:52.633
[SPEAKER_02]: Forgive me, Mr. Johnson, but this is about personal integrity and individual character.

24:53.053 --> 24:56.357
[SPEAKER_02]: Does the truth matter in this election?

24:57.012 --> 24:57.813
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it does.

24:58.254 --> 25:00.578
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think it very important.

25:00.598 --> 25:04.625
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it very important to hear from, I've been very clear about the deal that I've done.

25:04.866 --> 25:05.286
[SPEAKER_04]: There it is.

25:05.367 --> 25:06.028
[SPEAKER_04]: It's in black and white.

25:06.048 --> 25:06.709
[SPEAKER_04]: You can read it.

25:06.729 --> 25:07.250
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't know.

25:07.711 --> 25:09.394
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't know what Mr. Corbyn is proposing.

25:09.434 --> 25:10.596
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not just about Brexit.

25:10.616 --> 25:11.638
[SPEAKER_04]: He won't come clean.

25:11.658 --> 25:15.665
[SPEAKER_04]: He won't come clean with the electorate about what he is proposing to do.

25:15.685 --> 25:18.249
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Corbyn, allow Mr. Corbyn to respond, please.

25:18.269 --> 25:19.932
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

25:19.912 --> 25:23.838
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we've been very clear on our policies in relation to Europe.

25:24.338 --> 25:33.492
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we're also very clear on all the other policies that will be unveiled in our manifesto on Thursday and they will be accompanied by a fully costed Grey Book with it.

25:33.512 --> 25:48.233
[SPEAKER_17]: So every pledge we make will be fully funded because I believe the British people deserve that knowledge, deserve to know what we're going to do and deserve a government that is actually not going to preside over rising homelessness, increasing inequality and chaos in the NHS.

25:48.433 --> 25:49.615
[SPEAKER_17]: Instead they're going to invest

25:49.595 --> 25:51.134
[SPEAKER_17]: in the future of this country.

25:53.476 --> 25:58.803
[SPEAKER_02]: Gentlemen, will you take some personal responsibility for the way the debate has unfolded in politics in this country?

25:58.843 --> 26:06.593
[SPEAKER_02]: We know, of course, Mr Johnson, that people point to the fact that you promised 40 times on record we'd be out of the EU on October the 31st.

26:07.294 --> 26:15.103
[SPEAKER_02]: One of your former chief of staffs from your time as London mayor said that you'd betrayed every person you'd ever had any dealings with.

26:15.123 --> 26:21.091
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know, Mr Corbyn, there are big questions about anti-Semitism within Labour, for example.

26:22.373 --> 26:22.673
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that...

26:22.653 --> 26:33.389
[SPEAKER_02]: The board of deputies of British Jews have said, you and your allies have been responsible for turning a once great party into a cesspit of anti-Semitism, were their words.

26:33.469 --> 26:38.937
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you both take some responsibility for the way the debate has turned in this country?

26:38.977 --> 26:42.923
[SPEAKER_17]: Anti-Semitism is an absolute evil and scourge within our society.

26:44.033 --> 26:47.519
[SPEAKER_17]: Racism in any form is a scourge in our society.

26:48.120 --> 26:53.930
[SPEAKER_17]: I have taken action in my party where anyone has committed any anti-Semitic acts or made any anti-Semitic statements.

26:54.271 --> 26:58.939
[SPEAKER_17]: They are either suspended or expelled from the party, and we've investigated every single case.

26:59.199 --> 27:05.611
[SPEAKER_17]: We do take this very, very seriously indeed, because I do not want to live in a society where racism is rife.

27:05.911 --> 27:07.594
[SPEAKER_17]: I understand and recognize

27:07.574 --> 27:16.349
[SPEAKER_17]: the desperate history of the Jewish people in the 20th century, which came about from an unrestriction of anti-Semitism in the 1920s.

27:16.429 --> 27:22.759
[SPEAKER_17]: We've got to stand up against racism in any form in our society.

27:22.779 --> 27:28.148
[SPEAKER_02]: And on the question of telling the truth in politics, Mr Johnson, your response to that?

27:28.128 --> 27:30.071
[SPEAKER_02]: The points that I put you on, those issues.

27:30.191 --> 27:40.206
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I'm just listening with open mouth to what Jeremy Corbyn had to say about what he's done to stamp out anti-Semitism in the Labour Party.

27:40.226 --> 27:45.834
[SPEAKER_04]: Because I'm afraid it's a complete failure of leadership, what's happened in the Labour Party with anti-Semitism.

27:45.954 --> 27:52.043
[SPEAKER_04]: But the failure of leadership is even worse when you look at what is happening on their Brexit policy.

27:52.023 --> 28:03.282
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr Johnson, before we go any further on this, what the people of this country want to hear is clarity about whether he believes in the deal that he is proposing to do.

28:03.362 --> 28:08.310
[SPEAKER_02]: And that matters deeply to the people in Brussels who will be doing that deal.

28:08.290 --> 28:12.495
[SPEAKER_02]: This was a question from Fahad about personal integrity and character.

28:12.535 --> 28:15.739
[SPEAKER_02]: So let's just try to take stock before we go for the ad break.

28:15.759 --> 28:23.829
[SPEAKER_02]: There are many people and many politicians, indeed, that feel that the nastiness of political debate in this country has simply got out of control.

28:24.250 --> 28:32.360
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you two tonight look at one another, and no matter who becomes prime minister, make a gesture to improve things today?

28:32.620 --> 28:35.023
[SPEAKER_02]: Could you make a pledge and promise?

28:35.003 --> 28:39.630
[SPEAKER_17]: that whoever becomes Prime Minister improves the nature of debate in this country.

28:39.871 --> 28:49.206
[SPEAKER_17]: The debate in Parliament before Parliament was dissolved was vicious and horrible and some terrible remarks were made particularly to and about women MPs.

28:49.226 --> 28:58.581
[SPEAKER_17]: I asked the Speaker to convene a meeting of all party leaders, Mr Johnson sent a representative there and we agreed that this was unacceptable conduct and I absolutely agree with that.

28:58.561 --> 28:58.882
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

28:58.902 --> 29:02.468
[SPEAKER_17]: Will you both make a pledge to improve things?

29:02.488 --> 29:09.181
[SPEAKER_02]: And perhaps gentlemen, could you shake hands to make a pledge to improve politics?

29:09.201 --> 29:11.546
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

29:11.746 --> 29:13.129
[SPEAKER_04]: I strongly agree with what Jeremy said.

29:13.409 --> 29:13.770
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

29:13.790 --> 29:15.914
[SPEAKER_04]: Well then you might need to make some other statements as well.

29:15.934 --> 29:18.038
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, we've got a pledge from you both there.

29:18.440 --> 29:20.306
[SPEAKER_02]: After the break, a promise from us.

29:20.406 --> 29:23.535
[SPEAKER_02]: We will move on from Brexit to other issues this evening.

29:23.595 --> 29:30.576
[SPEAKER_02]: Next on Johnson versus Corbyn, we'll be talking about issues like the NHS, the economy, and possibly Prince Andrew.

33:15.314 --> 33:18.539
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, welcome back to Johnson versus Corbyn, the ITV debate.

33:18.559 --> 33:20.341
[SPEAKER_02]: In a moment, we'll take our next question.

33:20.382 --> 33:24.508
[SPEAKER_02]: But remember, this is just the first part of an ITV political double bill tonight.

33:24.708 --> 33:40.191
[SPEAKER_02]: At 10 o'clock tonight, we'll have the ITV election interviews, when the Lib Dem leader Joe Swinson, the SNP's Nicola Sturgeon, the Brexit Party's Nigel Farage, and Green Party co-leader Sean Berry will all be interviewed live by Nina Hossein.

33:40.171 --> 33:41.192
[SPEAKER_02]: Back to our debate.

33:41.372 --> 33:46.657
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's have our next question, and it comes from Omar Shahab, and it's on the NHS.

33:46.677 --> 33:48.098
[SPEAKER_02]: Omar.

33:48.118 --> 33:52.202
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm a hospital doctor, and I see firsthand the unsustainable pressure on the NHS.

33:53.583 --> 33:59.529
[SPEAKER_01]: Elderly patients stuck on trolleys in corridors, unacceptably long waiting times for operations.

34:00.209 --> 34:06.415
[SPEAKER_01]: Aside from pledging more money for the health service, how will you ensure that the health service can meet future demands?

34:06.995 --> 34:08.777
[SPEAKER_01]: And would that involve any privatisation?

34:09.871 --> 34:20.167
[SPEAKER_17]: I think the NHS is a wonderful and brilliant institution but it is suffering under the most incredible pressure.

34:20.708 --> 34:29.001
[SPEAKER_17]: The staff are unbelievably stressed by the job they have to do and the insufficiency of facilities to deal with it.

34:29.021 --> 34:33.027
[SPEAKER_17]: There are 33,000 nurse vacancies at the moment in the NHS.

34:33.530 --> 34:34.192
[SPEAKER_17]: I'll give a story.

34:34.212 --> 34:40.348
[SPEAKER_17]: Yesterday, a woman, a friend of mine, died at 6.30 yesterday morning from secondary breast cancer.

34:41.090 --> 34:47.667
[SPEAKER_17]: The day before, she'd gone to hospital at the recommendation of her GP in order to get urgent treatment.

34:48.208 --> 34:50.374
[SPEAKER_17]: She waited eight hours.

34:50.354 --> 34:56.122
[SPEAKER_17]: The nurses that were trying to help her were unable to get anyone to see her because they were under such strain and stress.

34:56.163 --> 35:02.131
[SPEAKER_17]: And so she recorded a video saying, please, in my memory, make sure nobody else goes through this pain.

35:02.151 --> 35:08.080
[SPEAKER_17]: We've got to fund our NHS properly and fill the vacancies and make sure it's there for all time.

35:08.300 --> 35:10.784
[SPEAKER_17]: It's one of the most civilized things about this country.

35:10.824 --> 35:12.126
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Chodron.

35:20.071 --> 35:25.618
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you Omar and I agree passionately with what you've said about the NHS.

35:25.658 --> 35:39.417
[SPEAKER_04]: It's absolutely vital that we support it and it is one of the single most beautiful and brilliant things about Britain and about our society and we are determined to fund it not just now but for the long term.

35:39.557 --> 35:41.860
[SPEAKER_04]: In this One Nation Conservative Government we're putting

35:41.840 --> 35:44.963
[SPEAKER_04]: record sums in £34 billion.

35:45.584 --> 35:55.996
[SPEAKER_04]: We are, as I said earlier on, we're not just upgrading 20 hospitals, but we are building 40 new hospitals as a result of the decisions taken by this government.

35:56.176 --> 35:57.998
[SPEAKER_04]: We will invest in GPs.

35:58.038 --> 36:02.222
[SPEAKER_04]: We'll have tens of thousands more nurses, 6,000 more GPs.

36:02.663 --> 36:11.813
[SPEAKER_04]: And our objective is to have a health service that is not just better for doctors and nurses, but better for patients as well.

36:11.793 --> 36:12.414
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

36:12.574 --> 36:15.700
[SPEAKER_04]: We can achieve that only if we have a strong economy.

36:15.720 --> 36:16.281
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

36:16.522 --> 36:18.425
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm afraid, which is what we do.

36:18.445 --> 36:19.728
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed.

36:20.169 --> 36:20.830
[SPEAKER_02]: Your time is up.

36:20.870 --> 36:22.373
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr Johnson.

36:22.393 --> 36:24.036
[SPEAKER_02]: Your time is up.

36:24.056 --> 36:25.098
[SPEAKER_17]: Mr Corbyn.

36:25.699 --> 36:30.628
[SPEAKER_17]: The problem is that the A&E performance is now at its worst ever.

36:30.608 --> 36:33.311
[SPEAKER_17]: There are 4 million people waiting for operations.

36:33.552 --> 36:37.096
[SPEAKER_17]: There are all the vacancies that have not been filled within the NHS.

36:37.196 --> 36:48.811
[SPEAKER_17]: The Health and Social Care Act allows the privatisation of services and indeed we have the nonsense of our National Health Service being taken to court by private operators because they didn't get contracts from it.

36:49.071 --> 36:55.840
[SPEAKER_17]: Let's end the privatisation within the NHS and instead have a fully funded NHS for all people.

36:55.820 --> 36:59.466
[SPEAKER_04]: Let Mr Johnson respond on that.

36:59.486 --> 37:00.829
[SPEAKER_04]: We are investing tax.

37:01.089 --> 37:02.352
[SPEAKER_04]: We are investing 30.

37:02.372 --> 37:04.375
[SPEAKER_20]: It's a specific question on privatization and private provision.

37:04.395 --> 37:06.860
[SPEAKER_04]: Of course we're not privatizing the NHS, nor do we have any.

37:06.880 --> 37:08.803
[SPEAKER_04]: And of course, we are investing 30.

37:09.104 --> 37:16.156
[SPEAKER_04]: Nor will the NHS, just let me repeat this point, nor will the NHS be ever up for sale in any negotiation.

37:16.176 --> 37:20.123
[SPEAKER_04]: Let me repeat that point and lay this more to rest.

37:20.103 --> 37:25.136
[SPEAKER_04]: Ladies and gentlemen, we will continue to fund the NHS massively as we are.

37:25.336 --> 37:28.464
[SPEAKER_04]: We can only do so because we have a strong and dynamic economy.

37:28.725 --> 37:33.317
[SPEAKER_04]: And by the way, don't forget that under Labour, they ruined the public finances.

37:33.838 --> 37:35.462
[SPEAKER_04]: They did.

37:35.442 --> 37:39.268
[SPEAKER_04]: Liam Byrne said himself there was no money left.

37:39.288 --> 37:42.612
[SPEAKER_04]: The economy has grown every year in the last nine years.

37:42.913 --> 37:56.312
[SPEAKER_04]: And what could be more ruinous for the NHS than a crackpot plan for a four-day week, which would add massively to the burdens not just of the NHS, but of every public service in the country.

37:56.332 --> 37:56.833
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

37:56.853 --> 37:57.975
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr. Corbyn, respond to this.

37:57.995 --> 38:03.002
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is the proposal for a four-day week for workers across the economy within 10 years of the Labour government.

38:02.982 --> 38:09.810
[SPEAKER_17]: It is about reducing the working week all across the economy, paid for by productivity increases all across.

38:09.891 --> 38:11.933
[SPEAKER_17]: Britain works longer than most.

38:12.734 --> 38:23.107
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, people need to be aware that actually a shorter working week is probably a good thing for their health and well-being, as is decent pay.

38:23.127 --> 38:32.078
[SPEAKER_17]: What I would also say to Mr Johnson is that his proposal for 40 new hospitals, which he grandly announced in July, turns out to be six reconfigurations

38:32.058 --> 38:34.826
[SPEAKER_04]: without any clarity as to where they're actually going to be.

38:35.568 --> 38:36.290
[SPEAKER_17]: OK, Mr Johnson.

38:36.551 --> 38:37.914
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, that is totally untrue.

38:37.955 --> 38:40.522
[SPEAKER_04]: We're doing 20 upgrades.

38:40.863 --> 38:45.235
[SPEAKER_04]: And yes, it is true that we are starting with six, but the seed funding has got in.

38:45.255 --> 38:47.080
[SPEAKER_04]: So where did the 40 come from?

38:47.060 --> 38:47.701
[SPEAKER_04]: hospitals.

38:47.721 --> 38:50.586
[SPEAKER_04]: And the investment is going in now.

38:50.846 --> 38:56.335
[SPEAKER_04]: And the only reason that investment can be made is because we have a robust economy.

38:56.616 --> 38:57.998
[SPEAKER_04]: And let me make another point.

38:58.258 --> 39:05.490
[SPEAKER_04]: The single biggest threat to our economy and our ability to fund the NHS is our failure to get Brexit

39:05.470 --> 39:08.256
[SPEAKER_04]: Ask the Governor that.

39:08.316 --> 39:11.061
[SPEAKER_04]: It's absolutely true.

39:11.122 --> 39:15.751
[SPEAKER_02]: It's hanging over this country and over this economy.

39:15.811 --> 39:18.316
[SPEAKER_02]: It's stopping investment coming in.

39:18.376 --> 39:23.547
[SPEAKER_02]: We need to get Brexit done and move on.

39:23.527 --> 39:27.952
[SPEAKER_02]: Sometimes it is there, provided by organizations that are not for profit.

39:27.992 --> 39:30.435
[SPEAKER_02]: It has extended capacity within the NHS.

39:30.455 --> 39:36.763
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you rule out any privatization in the NHS, any private provision within the NHS under...

39:36.783 --> 39:44.832
[SPEAKER_17]: The principle is to ensure that all people that work in the NHS are employed by the NHS on similar contracts across the NHS.

39:45.093 --> 39:46.194
[SPEAKER_17]: The internal market...

39:46.214 --> 39:46.635
[SPEAKER_17]: So, none.

39:46.855 --> 39:48.557
[SPEAKER_17]: ..must go within the NHS.

39:48.577 --> 39:52.842
[SPEAKER_17]: And what is happening is privatization of services

39:52.822 --> 39:58.650
[SPEAKER_17]: across the NHS, and I think that is very, very damaging to the whole principles of the NHS.

39:58.710 --> 40:07.602
[SPEAKER_17]: We also have problems of social care, which are not being addressed either, and there are about a million people waiting for social care at the present time.

40:07.622 --> 40:14.712
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. On that specific point, one quick answer, Mr Johnson, will there be a policy on social care in your manifesto, yes or no?

40:14.692 --> 40:27.467
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, they will, and we think that nobody should pay for their cost of their social care by selling their home, and everybody should have dignity and security in their old age.

40:27.487 --> 40:28.388
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, gentlemen.

40:28.408 --> 40:30.630
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much for your responses on that subject.

40:30.650 --> 40:38.159
[SPEAKER_02]: Now, of course, you will have heard that both have made significant spending pledges over the past couple of weeks, and not just on the NHS.

40:38.259 --> 40:41.983
[SPEAKER_02]: And Beverley Davis from Newport has a question related to this.

40:42.143 --> 40:42.724
[SPEAKER_02]: Beverley.

40:43.126 --> 40:46.132
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm a care home laundry assistant earning minimum wage.

40:46.693 --> 40:51.382
[SPEAKER_00]: I've worked all my life and have seen the real impact of austerity which neither of you have.

40:52.063 --> 40:54.027
[SPEAKER_00]: Now you say there's plenty to spend.

40:54.588 --> 40:58.194
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm concerned because neither of you have ever had to worry about money.

40:58.615 --> 41:01.280
[SPEAKER_00]: You'll throw it away on silly election giveaways.

41:01.661 --> 41:03.424
[SPEAKER_00]: What can you say to reassure me?

41:05.909 --> 41:06.450
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you very much indeed.

41:08.422 --> 41:13.053
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, we've had austerity for nine years in this country.

41:13.554 --> 41:16.440
[SPEAKER_17]: We've had a growth of billionaires in this country.

41:16.721 --> 41:19.187
[SPEAKER_17]: We've had a growth of extreme poverty in this country.

41:19.447 --> 41:24.859
[SPEAKER_17]: We've had a growth of personal debt from people trying to look after children, look after older people.

41:25.260 --> 41:27.325
[SPEAKER_17]: I think the first thing has to be

41:27.558 --> 41:45.001
[SPEAKER_17]: an increase in wages by having a £10 an hour living wage for all people, an end to zero hours contracts, and an investment strategy across the country that does give us an increase in manufacturing jobs all across Britain, which we're not having at the present time.

41:45.321 --> 41:50.688
[SPEAKER_17]: I think this election is a turning point in the way in which we're going to manage our economy in the future.

41:50.869 --> 41:53.532
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr Corbyn.

41:53.512 --> 42:08.334
[SPEAKER_04]: To answer the question directly about how we're handling public finances in this electoral period, I would just point out that I have shelved a plan to cut corporation tax, saving...

42:08.354 --> 42:09.857
[SPEAKER_04]: It's already the lowest in Europe.

42:09.877 --> 42:12.260
[SPEAKER_04]: He would whack it up to the highest in Europe.

42:12.380 --> 42:14.343
[SPEAKER_04]: But we've shelved that cut.

42:14.363 --> 42:21.294
[SPEAKER_04]: That gives us the ability to put another £6 billion into the NHS and other priorities.

42:21.354 --> 42:22.135
[SPEAKER_04]: And we will do that.

42:22.115 --> 42:24.760
[SPEAKER_04]: We can do that because we have a strong economy.

42:24.780 --> 42:29.970
[SPEAKER_04]: And what worries me about this country at the moment is that we are going to continue with this pointless paralysis.

42:29.990 --> 42:33.176
[SPEAKER_04]: I have no hesitation in repeating this point.

42:33.477 --> 42:40.209
[SPEAKER_04]: If we go on with more deadlock and division next year, if we fail to get Brexit done, then the economy will suffer.

42:40.229 --> 42:41.592
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the reality.

42:41.572 --> 42:45.116
[SPEAKER_02]: But Beverly's question was very specific.

42:45.156 --> 42:47.439
[SPEAKER_02]: She's saying now there seems to be plenty to spend.

42:47.479 --> 42:53.447
[SPEAKER_02]: She is concerned that because neither of you have had to worry about money, you'll throw it away on silly election giveaways.

42:53.627 --> 42:55.349
[SPEAKER_02]: Can we have a pledge here from both of you?

42:55.409 --> 42:58.753
[SPEAKER_02]: Simply, is austerity over in the United Kingdom, Mr Corbyn?

42:58.813 --> 43:00.495
[SPEAKER_17]: We will end austerity.

43:00.515 --> 43:01.757
[SPEAKER_17]: I'm absolutely clear about that.

43:01.737 --> 43:06.845
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, because it's so brutal on the lives of so many people.

43:06.865 --> 43:07.566
[SPEAKER_04]: Of course.

43:07.847 --> 43:18.925
[SPEAKER_04]: And I believe in spending, investing massively in our public services because we support, and which is what we are doing, but because we support a dynamic wealth-creating sector.

43:19.105 --> 43:28.420
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's why it's a good idea actually to believe in business, to support business, to support the wealth-creating sector of the economy.

43:28.400 --> 43:37.020
[SPEAKER_04]: Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party have actually said that they want to overthrow capitalism and to destroy the basis of wealth creation in this country.

43:37.321 --> 43:40.789
[SPEAKER_04]: I have to say, I think that would be disastrous for this country.

43:41.562 --> 44:00.246
[SPEAKER_17]: We will, over a period, over a parliament, increase corporation tax to around the levels it was in 2010 in order to reinvest properly in education, in order to pay for the ending of university tuition fees, to give every student a decent chance of going to university and life.

44:00.226 --> 44:07.376
[SPEAKER_17]: And we will start to address the grotesque levels of imbalance in our society.

44:07.676 --> 44:12.463
[SPEAKER_17]: We're a society of billionaires and the very poor, neither of which are right.

44:12.783 --> 44:15.106
[SPEAKER_02]: Both of you are proposing...

44:15.127 --> 44:18.892
[SPEAKER_02]: Both of you gentlemen are proposing extraordinary levels of borrowing.

44:19.032 --> 44:24.499
[SPEAKER_02]: At the last election, we were told by your predecessor, Mr Johnson, that there was no magic money tree.

44:24.519 --> 44:26.883
[SPEAKER_02]: Have you found a magic money tree, Mr Johnson?

44:27.003 --> 44:30.047
[SPEAKER_02]: And have you found perhaps more than one of them, Mr Corbyn?

44:30.955 --> 44:36.564
[SPEAKER_04]: No, we are operating... Money forest he's got.

44:37.065 --> 44:52.609
[SPEAKER_04]: We're operating within strict fiscal discipline and yes, of course, we're investing now in the NHS and we're investing in our policing and investing in education because we have the fiscal headroom to do so.

44:52.589 --> 45:02.679
[SPEAKER_04]: We're also going to do fantastic things for this country with infrastructure, with uniting the whole country, with better high-speed rail, with telecommunications.

45:02.959 --> 45:04.741
[SPEAKER_04]: We're going to do fantastic things for this country.

45:04.761 --> 45:07.463
[SPEAKER_04]: You can only do that if interest rates are low.

45:07.804 --> 45:15.011
[SPEAKER_04]: And the rate at which Labour would borrow would push up interest rates for every household in the country.

45:15.091 --> 45:15.291
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

45:15.311 --> 45:17.093
[SPEAKER_20]: A response from that particular point.

45:17.113 --> 45:20.436
[SPEAKER_17]: The reality of austerity has been to hit the

45:20.416 --> 45:41.888
[SPEAKER_17]: The funds of local authorities has meant the life chances of children have been damaged by underfunding schools, headteachers going out collecting money in order to keep a school going, young people with no after-school clubs, no youth centre to go to, and the levels of dislocation and poverty in so many areas of Britain deliberately, because of austerity, must and will change.

45:41.928 --> 45:47.997
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, we will invest in education.

45:48.017 --> 45:48.537
[SPEAKER_02]: We will invest in housing.

45:48.558 --> 45:49.058
[SPEAKER_02]: We will invest in health.

45:49.078 --> 45:49.579
[SPEAKER_02]: Of course, all of this...

45:50.504 --> 45:58.818
[SPEAKER_02]: All of this, gentlemen, all of this, gentlemen, is, of course, predicated on what sort of Brexit deal either of you might be able to achieve.

45:59.238 --> 46:05.068
[SPEAKER_02]: But we're going to move on to some other subject matters now in our debate, something a little different.

46:05.088 --> 46:17.068
[SPEAKER_02]: We have had hundreds and hundreds of questions from ITV viewers, and now we're going to have a quick-fire section on a wide variety of issues to try to learn a little bit more about where the leaders stand on those other issues.

46:17.048 --> 46:25.098
[SPEAKER_02]: So if you could say in a few words as possible, perhaps even a yes or no, gentlemen, given that we're looking at the clock... How do you define a few words?

46:25.178 --> 46:27.280
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, just editing.

46:27.601 --> 46:30.945
[SPEAKER_02]: One, two, or just give us a clear, precise answer.

46:31.706 --> 46:34.069
[SPEAKER_02]: The first question is Sue from Leeds.

46:34.349 --> 46:36.372
[SPEAKER_02]: Is the monarchy fit for purpose?

46:36.392 --> 46:37.052
[SPEAKER_02]: Jeremy Corbyn.

46:37.092 --> 46:38.054
[SPEAKER_17]: Needs a bit of improvement.

46:42.099 --> 46:42.499
APPLAUSE Mr Johnson.

46:44.234 --> 46:47.320
[SPEAKER_04]: The institution of the monarchy is beyond reproach.

46:49.144 --> 46:52.972
[SPEAKER_02]: Is Prince Andrew fit for purpose?

46:54.295 --> 47:00.488
[SPEAKER_17]: Before we discuss Prince Andrew, I think we should discuss the victims that are there because of what Epstein was doing.

47:01.497 --> 47:16.681
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think there are very, very serious questions that must be answered, and nobody should be above the law, but the primary position ought to be the proper treatment of those people who are victims of the most appalling behaviour by, apparently, Epstein and many others.

47:16.701 --> 47:20.086
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, Mr Johnson.

47:20.106 --> 47:29.901
[SPEAKER_04]: I think all our sympathies should be, obviously, with the victims of Geoffrey Epstein, and the law must certainly take its course.

47:30.202 --> 47:39.599
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed of course and we know that we've heard from Prince Andrew this week and we'll move on now to our next question from Andrew from Liverpool.

47:39.920 --> 47:43.426
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you agree that climate change is the biggest issue in our country today?

47:43.887 --> 47:44.428
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr. Johnson.

47:44.909 --> 47:49.898
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it's a colossal issue for the entire world and the UK

47:50.452 --> 47:58.526
[SPEAKER_04]: The UK is meeting that challenge with the most far-reaching ambition to get to carbon neutral by 2050.

47:59.287 --> 48:05.979
[SPEAKER_04]: And I know you don't want me to say this, but we need to get Brexit done in order to deliver on those priorities.

48:05.999 --> 48:07.702
[SPEAKER_20]: OK, Mr Corbyn, is it the biggest issue?

48:07.722 --> 48:09.184
[SPEAKER_20]: Is it the biggest issue?

48:09.204 --> 48:11.869
[SPEAKER_17]: It's the most massive issue facing the whole world.

48:11.849 --> 48:35.140
[SPEAKER_17]: when the poorest people in the poorest countries lose out because of flooding and unusual weather patterns, when we have unusual weather patterns in this country, when we have extreme levels of air pollution, we have to have a green industrial revolution where we invest for the future in sustainable industries and jobs and prevent the continuing damage to our natural world and our environment.

48:40.267 --> 48:42.110
[SPEAKER_02]: Which current...

48:42.130 --> 48:43.893
[SPEAKER_02]: This is a question from Tony from Bristol.

48:43.913 --> 48:46.657
[SPEAKER_02]: Which current foreign leader do you most admire, Mr Johnson?

48:47.278 --> 48:48.339
[SPEAKER_04]: Current foreign leader?

48:48.960 --> 48:49.942
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I...

48:50.242 --> 48:51.124
[SPEAKER_04]: It's a very good question.

48:51.144 --> 48:51.825
[SPEAKER_04]: I think I...

48:53.006 --> 48:57.313
[SPEAKER_04]: I like the EU 27, all of them, because... LAUGHTER

48:57.867 --> 49:02.112
[SPEAKER_04]: They did me a fantastic deal, which enables us to come out of the EU.

49:02.653 --> 49:05.717
[SPEAKER_04]: And I have yet to hear, and I'm going to ask him again.

49:05.957 --> 49:12.525
[SPEAKER_04]: I've yet to hear what the leader of the opposition would do with this deal and whether he'd campaign for me or remain.

49:12.545 --> 49:15.529
[SPEAKER_02]: I feel obliged to ask this question.

49:15.829 --> 49:22.998
[SPEAKER_17]: I think the person I admire most in the world at the present time is the General Secretary of the United Nations, Guterres, trying to bring the world together.

49:23.018 --> 49:24.600
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you very much indeed.

49:27.365 --> 49:32.510
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, we didn't get quite through as many as we thought we might, gentlemen.

49:32.530 --> 49:39.816
[SPEAKER_02]: But we're going to have, before our concluding statements, perhaps time for one more short seasonal question.

49:39.936 --> 49:42.378
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is from Ben West in Kent.

49:43.319 --> 49:49.705
[SPEAKER_11]: I think we should all learn to be a little more kind to each other, including those we disagree with.

49:50.346 --> 49:56.511
[SPEAKER_11]: With this in mind, and leaving politics aside for a moment, what present would you leave under the Christmas tree for each other this year?

49:58.448 --> 50:02.153
[SPEAKER_02]: Leaving politics aside, gentlemen.

50:02.233 --> 50:07.660
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, leaving politics aside, what gift would you leave for Mr. Johnson under the Christmas tree?

50:07.680 --> 50:09.762
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I know Mr. Johnson likes a good read.

50:10.443 --> 50:18.033
[SPEAKER_17]: So what I would probably leave under the tree for him would be a Christmas carol by Charles Dickens.

50:18.053 --> 50:20.496
[SPEAKER_17]: And he can then understand how nasty Scrooge was.

50:21.337 --> 50:21.537
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

50:22.006 --> 50:22.827
[SPEAKER_17]: Mr. Johnson?

50:23.607 --> 50:36.980
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I think, well, I would probably leave a copy of, since you want a literary effort, a copy of my brilliant Brexit deal, which allows us to come back.

50:37.000 --> 50:37.280
[SPEAKER_04]: Non-political.

50:37.300 --> 50:37.580
[SPEAKER_04]: Non-political.

50:37.600 --> 50:37.961
[SPEAKER_04]: I will wait.

50:38.221 --> 50:41.204
[SPEAKER_04]: Maybe by next year, we will be able to see his own Brexit deal.

50:41.224 --> 50:42.885
[SPEAKER_04]: Non-political, Mr. Johnson.

50:42.905 --> 50:43.526
[SPEAKER_04]: Non-political.

50:43.546 --> 50:48.550
[SPEAKER_04]: What I think, Mr. Corbyn, Mr. Corbyn shares my love of plants and trees.

50:48.851 --> 50:50.292
[SPEAKER_04]: I think maybe some...

50:50.272 --> 50:51.815
[SPEAKER_04]: Maybe your little cardboard buses, maybe.

50:51.835 --> 50:52.315
[SPEAKER_04]: Some dams and jams.

50:52.335 --> 50:53.397
[SPEAKER_04]: Some dams and jams.

50:53.417 --> 50:54.980
[SPEAKER_04]: Some dams and jams.

50:55.100 --> 50:57.464
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, gentlemen, thank you very much indeed for that.

50:57.564 --> 50:58.506
[SPEAKER_04]: He doesn't even want my dams and jams.

50:59.127 --> 50:59.568
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

50:59.588 --> 51:01.891
[SPEAKER_02]: A fascinating 50 minutes of debate.

51:01.992 --> 51:07.240
[SPEAKER_02]: I will now ask Jeremy Corbyn and Boris Johnson for a very short concluding statement.

51:07.361 --> 51:08.803
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn first.

51:09.593 --> 51:15.140
[SPEAKER_17]: You've seen tonight the real choice you'll have in this election, and your voice must be heard.

51:15.760 --> 51:19.545
[SPEAKER_17]: If you haven't registered to vote, please go online and do it now.

51:20.205 --> 51:22.588
[SPEAKER_17]: This is a once-in-a-generation election.

51:23.149 --> 51:26.933
[SPEAKER_17]: To end privatisation and give the National Health Service the funding it needs.

51:27.394 --> 51:29.997
[SPEAKER_17]: To give people the final say and get Brexit sorted.

51:30.297 --> 51:33.561
[SPEAKER_17]: To tackle the climate emergency that threatens our futures.

51:33.942 --> 51:37.105
[SPEAKER_17]: To invest in good jobs in every region and nation of our country.

51:37.606 --> 51:39.448
[SPEAKER_17]: I ask that you vote for hope

51:39.428 --> 51:57.235
[SPEAKER_17]: and vote for Labour on the 12th of December.

51:58.362 --> 51:59.964
[SPEAKER_04]: Our choice is very simple.

52:00.004 --> 52:10.961
[SPEAKER_04]: We can get Brexit done, or we can spend another groundhog year with another referendum when Mr Corbyn, you've heard tonight, cannot answer the fundamental question.

52:11.622 --> 52:13.445
[SPEAKER_04]: Is he for remain or leave?

52:13.645 --> 52:18.492
[SPEAKER_04]: And what price would he pay to secure Nicola Sturgeon's support to enter Number 10?

52:18.512 --> 52:24.201
[SPEAKER_04]: And if he can't answer those questions tonight, I don't think he's fit to lead our country.

52:24.181 --> 52:29.869
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's end the dither and delay the deadlock and the divisions.

52:29.889 --> 52:39.061
[SPEAKER_04]: And if we have a working majority, a conservative majority, I pledge we will have a parliament that works for you, that focuses on the NHS and the cost of living.

52:39.241 --> 52:49.274
[SPEAKER_04]: Because when we get Brexit done by January the 31st, we will go forward as a united and confident nation that has shown our faith in the judgment of our people.

52:49.615 --> 52:52.519
[SPEAKER_20]: Out of time.

52:52.539 --> 52:53.580
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr. Johnson, Mr. Corbyn, thank you very much indeed.

52:54.353 --> 52:59.462
[SPEAKER_02]: That is the end of the first part of our live political programming tonight.

52:59.522 --> 53:03.830
[SPEAKER_02]: An hour from now, we'll hear from four more party leaders on what they think matters at this election.

53:03.870 --> 53:05.693
[SPEAKER_02]: That's the ITV election interviews.

53:05.773 --> 53:10.101
[SPEAKER_02]: But for now, from Salford, from all of us here, goodnight.

53:14.941 --> 53:21.049
[SPEAKER_08]: So the first head-to-head debate has made the history books, but now the battle over how they'll be written.

53:21.169 --> 53:23.873
[SPEAKER_08]: Welcome to the ITV debate unspun.

53:23.933 --> 53:35.929
[SPEAKER_08]: We're live backstage here in the spin room where both camps watched their candidates up there on the big screen and are now bending the ears of journalists trying to put the polish on their leader's performance.

53:36.009 --> 53:37.931
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll go and speak to them in just a moment.

53:37.991 --> 53:40.415
[SPEAKER_08]: But first, we want your snap verdict.

53:40.435 --> 53:43.699
[SPEAKER_08]: Head over to at ITV News on Twitter, where I am posting a poll

53:43.679 --> 53:48.708
[SPEAKER_08]: Right now, tell us who you think won tonight's debate, Jeremy Corbyn or Boris Johnson.

53:48.728 --> 53:54.219
[SPEAKER_08]: We'll leave that unscientific poll up for 10 minutes or so and bring you the results later in the show.

53:54.659 --> 53:58.887
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, let us see what everyone in the room made of that debate.

53:58.987 --> 54:01.913
[SPEAKER_08]: So just to give you a... Michael Gove, what was that?

54:02.133 --> 54:03.055
[SPEAKER_08]: A victory for Boris?

54:03.035 --> 54:04.237
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, 100%.

54:04.397 --> 54:05.419
[SPEAKER_08]: Absolutely brilliant.

54:05.459 --> 54:08.063
[SPEAKER_06]: And I hear you were playing Jeremy Corbyn in the rehearsals as well.

54:08.203 --> 54:13.811
[SPEAKER_06]: No, I was watching that debate, and there was only one prime minister on that stage, and that was Boris Johnson.

54:14.172 --> 54:22.084
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn, when he was asked 10 times how he would campaign in his Brexit referendum that he wants to have, simply couldn't answer the question.

54:22.384 --> 54:24.848
[SPEAKER_06]: He couldn't say whether or not he would back Leave or Remain.

54:25.228 --> 54:26.570
[SPEAKER_06]: That is not leadership.

54:26.951 --> 54:28.333
[SPEAKER_06]: That is a vacuum.

54:28.313 --> 54:33.860
[SPEAKER_06]: It's also the case that he said that we're going to have another referendum, as well as the EU referendum, on Scotland.

54:34.080 --> 54:35.201
[SPEAKER_06]: He made it perfectly clear.

54:35.221 --> 54:37.384
[SPEAKER_08]: No, he ruled it out in the first few years of a Labour government.

54:37.404 --> 54:39.186
[SPEAKER_06]: And look, Boris Johnson had his problems too.

54:39.427 --> 54:41.149
[SPEAKER_06]: No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

54:41.169 --> 54:45.194
[SPEAKER_06]: He was perfectly clear that he was going to accept a referendum in Scotland.

54:45.434 --> 54:53.764
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's also the case that he made it perfectly clear that we're going to have a four-day week in the NHS as well, putting patient safety at risk.

54:53.744 --> 54:57.330
[SPEAKER_06]: and diverting money away from helping those who need it.

54:57.370 --> 55:03.220
[SPEAKER_08]: Does it not worry you that there was open laughter from the audience when Boris Johnson talked about telling the truth and trusting politics?

55:03.240 --> 55:07.748
[SPEAKER_06]: There was open laughter at Jeremy Corbyn's failure to answer the questions on Brexit.

55:07.768 --> 55:09.251
[SPEAKER_06]: People want Brexit done.

55:09.271 --> 55:10.673
[SPEAKER_06]: They want an end to paralysis.

55:10.733 --> 55:13.558
[SPEAKER_06]: The reason we're having this election is because we have a broken

55:13.792 --> 55:15.174
[SPEAKER_06]: Parliament and people want progress.

55:15.454 --> 55:16.576
[SPEAKER_06]: We've got a great Brexit deal.

55:16.917 --> 55:23.326
[SPEAKER_06]: What we had from Jeremy Corbyn tonight was a terrifying display of intellectual vacuity.

55:23.346 --> 55:30.957
[SPEAKER_06]: He simply has no answer to the essential question, does he want in any new referendum that he says he's going to secure

55:30.937 --> 55:34.201
[SPEAKER_06]: Does he want us to be inside the European Union or out?

55:34.221 --> 55:35.422
[SPEAKER_06]: OK, OK. No answers.

55:35.602 --> 55:36.163
[SPEAKER_06]: No leadership.

55:36.183 --> 55:37.745
[SPEAKER_08]: Joining us live on ITV.

55:37.785 --> 55:39.246
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, we better let him do a few more interviews.

55:39.266 --> 55:41.509
[SPEAKER_08]: I hadn't quite expected that snap reaction there.

55:41.669 --> 55:44.512
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's try and squeeze through here, through the scrum.

55:44.913 --> 55:47.856
[SPEAKER_08]: There are other parties here in the spin room tonight, too, of course.

55:47.876 --> 55:50.219
[SPEAKER_08]: We've got the Green Party over here.

55:50.239 --> 55:51.580
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening to you, Natalie Bennett.

55:51.600 --> 55:52.281
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening to you.

55:52.301 --> 55:52.381
[SPEAKER_08]: Hi.

55:52.421 --> 55:53.282
[SPEAKER_08]: What did you make of the debate?

55:53.262 --> 55:54.825
[SPEAKER_12]: It was very, very loud.

55:54.865 --> 55:58.632
[SPEAKER_12]: There was a lot of shouting and of course a great deal of it was coming from Boris Johnson.

55:58.832 --> 55:59.614
[SPEAKER_12]: It was really noticeable.

55:59.634 --> 56:00.134
[SPEAKER_12]: You looked at that.

56:00.195 --> 56:02.198
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, I've been chaired by Juliette Tringham.

56:02.238 --> 56:03.901
[SPEAKER_12]: I know she's an enormously strong chair.

56:03.941 --> 56:05.925
[SPEAKER_08]: Of course, you took part in the debates in 2015.

56:05.985 --> 56:07.508
[SPEAKER_12]: Exactly, that's right.

56:07.528 --> 56:11.355
[SPEAKER_12]: And it was good that she was there because she was eventually bringing Boris Johnson under control.

56:11.435 --> 56:12.537
[SPEAKER_12]: But he was trying to

56:12.517 --> 56:15.802
[SPEAKER_12]: all the time, go over his time, he was trying to shout over the top of her.

56:16.062 --> 56:26.898
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think, you know, the real mood of that is Jeremy Corbyn came out as, you know, speaking from the heart, like when he was talking about the NHS, you know, it was, it was very loud and I'm not sure it really shed a lot of light on anything very much.

56:27.298 --> 56:30.423
[SPEAKER_12]: But, you know, it was definitely, I would call it for Jeremy Corbyn.

56:30.503 --> 56:31.204
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, thank you very much.

56:31.224 --> 56:35.049
[SPEAKER_08]: Of course, you've got chance to take part in the debate later this after, this evening.

56:35.069 --> 56:37.673
[SPEAKER_08]: Sian Berry will be on that programme at 10 o'clock tonight.

56:37.994 --> 56:41.038
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, let's go and see what some of the journalists thought.

56:41.828 --> 56:42.629
[SPEAKER_08]: of that debate.

56:43.370 --> 56:52.623
[SPEAKER_08]: So these seats are where all the lobby journalists are currently filing their verdict, quickly, ahead of their nine o'clock deadline, isn't it, for you guys?

56:52.683 --> 56:53.084
[SPEAKER_08]: Nine o'clock?

56:53.905 --> 56:54.245
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, around that.

56:54.265 --> 56:56.168
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, Nicola Bartlett from the Mirror, what did you make of it?

56:56.909 --> 56:58.912
[SPEAKER_18]: I think it was a surprise, actually.

56:59.553 --> 57:04.900
[SPEAKER_18]: Jeremy Corbyn seemed a lot more comfortable in that set-up than perhaps anticipated.

57:04.880 --> 57:10.828
[SPEAKER_18]: And they both seemed to be, it seemed very different from when they square off over the dispatch box.

57:11.710 --> 57:15.876
[SPEAKER_18]: A few jokes there from Boris Johnson, but also a few from Jeremy Corbyn.

57:16.136 --> 57:19.941
[SPEAKER_18]: And there were some lines which did seem to land better than others.

57:20.081 --> 57:24.728
[SPEAKER_18]: This coalition, the accusation that Jeremy Corbyn would go into coalition.

57:24.708 --> 57:30.514
[SPEAKER_18]: and the Coalition of Chaos, and Jeremy Corbyn sort of quick as a flash said, well, we've already had nine years of that.

57:30.934 --> 57:39.784
[SPEAKER_18]: You know, conversely, there was a lot of laughter when he talked about his Brexit position, saying it was clear, the audience laughed at that because they don't think it's clear at all.

57:40.524 --> 57:43.768
[SPEAKER_18]: So it's difficult to just kind of, you know, see who won.

57:43.788 --> 57:45.610
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you think it's kind of a score draw, then, in your view?

57:45.630 --> 57:46.170
[SPEAKER_18]: A little bit.

57:46.230 --> 57:48.232
[SPEAKER_18]: I mean, I did love the exchange at the end.

57:48.292 --> 57:50.935
[SPEAKER_18]: I mean, brilliant question about Christmas presents.

57:50.915 --> 57:56.206
[SPEAKER_18]: And Boris Johnson sounded almost plaintive when he said, you know, Jeremy Corbyn won't even take my jam.

57:56.907 --> 58:03.100
[SPEAKER_18]: But, you know, sometimes it's those unexpected questions that kind of show the true personalities.

58:03.120 --> 58:04.102
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, all right, Nicola, thank you.

58:04.142 --> 58:05.264
[SPEAKER_08]: And Matt Dathan from The Sun.

58:05.965 --> 58:06.747
[SPEAKER_08]: Who do you reckon won?

58:06.946 --> 58:09.810
[SPEAKER_09]: Neither to be honest, probably the audience.

58:09.991 --> 58:18.464
[SPEAKER_09]: I think we saw a lot of the public's anger at the way that British politics has been run for the last three years to be honest.

58:18.504 --> 58:26.035
[SPEAKER_09]: We had two audience members who really kind of showed that anger.

58:26.015 --> 58:30.027
[SPEAKER_09]: But it was much more conciliatory than I thought it would be.

58:30.609 --> 58:34.761
[SPEAKER_09]: They even shook hands at one point, pledging to, you know, improve the quality of the debate.

58:34.801 --> 58:37.609
[SPEAKER_09]: I very much doubt that will happen, but we'll have to wait and see.

58:37.629 --> 58:38.071
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, alright.

58:38.111 --> 58:40.277
[SPEAKER_08]: Matt Nicola, thank you very much.

58:40.392 --> 58:44.980
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's head back up the room now, asking our cameraman to do a bit of a shuffle here.

58:45.000 --> 58:47.404
[SPEAKER_08]: It's actually really rammed in this spin room this time.

58:47.724 --> 58:57.019
[SPEAKER_08]: We think this is the busiest the spin room has been since the 2015 debates, with interest from around the world actually, even interest from as far flung as Israel.

58:57.861 --> 59:03.430
[SPEAKER_08]: Journalists from across the UK, of course, have all come here to listen to the various spin on

59:03.410 --> 59:06.034
[SPEAKER_08]: on the debate from the various parties.

59:06.494 --> 59:07.376
[SPEAKER_08]: Who else have we got here?

59:07.396 --> 59:15.887
[SPEAKER_08]: So we've got Tom Brake from the Lib Dems over there doing a bit of spinning on behalf of Joe Swinson, who will also be appearing on our programme at 10 o'clock tonight.

59:16.608 --> 59:21.675
[SPEAKER_08]: And over here is Lee Cain, Head of Communications for Number 10.

59:22.336 --> 59:23.578
[SPEAKER_08]: And

59:23.558 --> 59:28.727
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's get some reaction, some political reaction too from our guests who've kindly agreed to join me this evening.

59:28.747 --> 59:31.812
[SPEAKER_08]: We've got Dawn Butler from Labour and Priti Patel from the Conservative Party.

59:31.832 --> 59:32.914
[SPEAKER_08]: Good evening to both of you.

59:33.314 --> 59:34.757
[SPEAKER_08]: A pretty packed spin room tonight.

59:35.638 --> 59:36.720
[SPEAKER_08]: First questions first.

59:37.141 --> 59:40.646
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy Corbyn, I think fair to say, Dawn Butler went into this as the underdog.

59:41.127 --> 59:43.491
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you think he's not emerged as the underdog too?

59:43.825 --> 59:55.084
[SPEAKER_19]: I think he's emerged as a man of integrity, a man of honesty, a man who's got the country's best interests at heart, a man who's got the policies at the turning point of our country.

59:55.124 --> 59:58.189
[SPEAKER_19]: This is the most important election in a generation.

59:58.509 --> 01:00:01.755
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think Boris Johnson came across as a deeply dishonest man.

01:00:02.997 --> 01:00:06.162
[SPEAKER_08]: Jeremy Corbyn did struggle to land his point quite a few times, though.

01:00:06.182 --> 01:00:08.466
[SPEAKER_08]: Do you really think he's managed to close the gap tonight?

01:00:08.598 --> 01:00:10.840
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, it wasn't about landing points.

01:00:11.161 --> 01:00:12.182
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that what the debate's all about?

01:00:12.202 --> 01:00:13.583
[SPEAKER_19]: It's not about soundbites.

01:00:13.603 --> 01:00:18.108
[SPEAKER_19]: This is about telling the country what a Labour government will deliver for the country.

01:00:18.348 --> 01:00:19.770
[SPEAKER_19]: Boris Johnson was just full of bluster.

01:00:19.810 --> 01:00:23.814
[SPEAKER_19]: Everything he tried to sort of cloak and umbrella in like a fake Brexit debate.

01:00:23.854 --> 01:00:25.316
[SPEAKER_19]: It's just pure fake news.

01:00:25.636 --> 01:00:28.139
[SPEAKER_19]: Boris Johnson talked about the NHS with compassion.

01:00:28.419 --> 01:00:30.221
[SPEAKER_19]: He talked about nurses and doctors.

01:00:30.241 --> 01:00:31.342
[SPEAKER_19]: He talked about schools.

01:00:31.362 --> 01:00:32.884
[SPEAKER_19]: He talked about all the policies.

01:00:32.864 --> 01:00:35.488
[SPEAKER_19]: that's going to make the difference in real people's lives.

01:00:35.788 --> 01:00:39.373
[SPEAKER_19]: Boris Johnson isn't even in touch with his own feelings, let alone the rest of the country.

01:00:39.633 --> 01:00:40.394
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that true, Priti Patel?

01:00:40.414 --> 01:00:41.396
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, absolutely not.

01:00:41.436 --> 01:00:48.045
[SPEAKER_03]: And quite frankly, what we saw this evening, there's only one Prime Minister in the room and on the stage tonight, and that was Boris Johnson.

01:00:48.406 --> 01:00:56.937
[SPEAKER_03]: He was unequivocal, very clear that the Conservative Party, under his leadership, is the only party that will lead a government that will get Brexit done.

01:00:57.018 --> 01:00:59.461
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's what the British public are crying out for right now.

01:00:59.481 --> 01:01:00.222
[SPEAKER_00]: But how can he get Brexit done?

01:01:00.202 --> 01:01:01.725
[SPEAKER_03]: Dawn, let me finish please.

01:01:01.785 --> 01:01:02.566
[SPEAKER_03]: Dawn, I didn't interrupt.

01:01:02.646 --> 01:01:03.227
[SPEAKER_03]: Let me finish.

01:01:03.608 --> 01:01:11.241
[SPEAKER_03]: And with that, once we get Brexit done, and this is the key thing, and to be fair, Jeremy Corbyn could not even answer what he was going to do on Brexit.

01:01:11.261 --> 01:01:12.663
[SPEAKER_03]: He refused nine times.

01:01:12.984 --> 01:01:22.800
[SPEAKER_03]: And when we speak about trust in politics and the breakdown in politics and the gridlock we've seen in Westminster, the fact that Jeremy Corbyn couldn't even outline his own Brexit policy.

01:01:22.780 --> 01:01:24.523
[SPEAKER_19]: Because that's exactly what he wanted.

01:01:24.543 --> 01:01:26.546
[SPEAKER_19]: That was exactly the line that they prepared.

01:01:26.927 --> 01:01:28.469
[SPEAKER_19]: That's exactly the line they wanted to say.

01:01:28.489 --> 01:01:30.212
[SPEAKER_19]: But let me answer it for you, pretty.

01:01:30.252 --> 01:01:30.913
[SPEAKER_19]: The thing is this.

01:01:31.274 --> 01:01:35.421
[SPEAKER_19]: Jeremy Corbyn, as Prime Minister, is not for him to deliver what he wants.

01:01:35.741 --> 01:01:37.664
[SPEAKER_19]: It's for him to deliver what the country wants.

01:01:38.025 --> 01:01:41.531
[SPEAKER_19]: And that's the difference between Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn.

01:01:41.551 --> 01:01:43.795
[SPEAKER_19]: Jeremy Corbyn will deliver what the country wants.

01:01:43.875 --> 01:01:46.279
[SPEAKER_03]: And the country voted in 2016 for the referendum to leave.

01:01:46.299 --> 01:01:49.564
[SPEAKER_19]: Boris Johnson stopped his own Brexit deal in Parliament.

01:01:49.544 --> 01:01:51.868
[SPEAKER_19]: Let's tell the country the truth.

01:01:51.888 --> 01:01:55.413
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm so irritated by that man, I cannot tell you.

01:01:55.494 --> 01:01:58.138
[SPEAKER_08]: And actually, the audience seemed fairly irritated at times too, Priti Patel.

01:01:58.158 --> 01:02:02.905
[SPEAKER_08]: I mean, the audience laughed down Boris Johnson when he was asked about trust and whether he tells the truth.

01:02:02.926 --> 01:02:09.055
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I think it's worth relating and noting the fact the audience also laughed at Mr Corbyn on his Brexit policy as well.

01:02:09.115 --> 01:02:11.199
[SPEAKER_03]: It was absolutely clear and abundant.

01:02:11.539 --> 01:02:13.763
[SPEAKER_03]: There is no clear policy on Brexit.

01:02:13.783 --> 01:02:15.045
[SPEAKER_03]: And I have to say, Dawn,

01:02:15.025 --> 01:02:16.508
[SPEAKER_03]: The British public voted in 2016.

01:02:16.708 --> 01:02:18.592
[SPEAKER_03]: It was called the EU referendum.

01:02:18.612 --> 01:02:19.573
[SPEAKER_03]: They voted to leave.

01:02:19.994 --> 01:02:30.434
[SPEAKER_03]: And actually, what kind of democracy do we live in if the Labour Party are effectively proposing for next year that we'd have two referendums, one on the EU and a second one on the Scottish referendum?

01:02:30.574 --> 01:02:32.878
[SPEAKER_03]: So you don't want the public to make the final decision then?

01:02:32.918 --> 01:02:34.862
[SPEAKER_03]: We have had our referendum.

01:02:35.082 --> 01:02:37.607
[SPEAKER_03]: You don't want the public to make the final decision?

01:02:37.587 --> 01:02:41.672
[SPEAKER_03]: The country voted to leave, and the country want to get Brexit done.

01:02:41.993 --> 01:02:45.337
[SPEAKER_03]: And I travel the country every day, and I speak to members of the public every day.

01:02:45.638 --> 01:02:48.001
[SPEAKER_03]: And I can tell you now, Paul, they want Brexit done.

01:02:48.041 --> 01:02:51.285
[SPEAKER_19]: Do you want the public to have a people's vote and make the final decision, yes or no?

01:02:51.565 --> 01:02:52.467
[SPEAKER_19]: Because we do.

01:02:52.487 --> 01:02:55.150
[SPEAKER_19]: And we are the only party that wants to do that.

01:02:55.410 --> 01:02:59.536
[SPEAKER_19]: We are the only party that is saying to the country, you will make the final decision.

01:02:59.836 --> 01:03:03.962
[SPEAKER_19]: And what will be on the ballot paper is a credible leave option and a remain option.

01:03:04.302 --> 01:03:06.565
[SPEAKER_19]: Very clear, very straightforward.

01:03:06.545 --> 01:03:10.894
[SPEAKER_03]: So, Dawn, I'm delighted you've confirmed tonight that there will be a second referendum under Labour government next year.

01:03:10.914 --> 01:03:11.315
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, there will.

01:03:11.335 --> 01:03:13.199
[SPEAKER_03]: That is exactly what the British people don't want.

01:03:13.219 --> 01:03:17.628
[SPEAKER_03]: They want us to get Brexit done so we can carry on doing what we're doing.

01:03:17.668 --> 01:03:20.033
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm glad you now understand our Brexit policy.

01:03:20.274 --> 01:03:22.058
[SPEAKER_19]: Hopefully the rest of the Conservatives will listen to you.

01:03:22.078 --> 01:03:25.385
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, there was laughter tonight about whether the audience understood your Brexit policy.

01:03:25.425 --> 01:03:26.106
[SPEAKER_13]: Let's hope so.

01:03:26.086 --> 01:03:28.109
[SPEAKER_08]: I've allowed you two to have a good old debate this evening.

01:03:28.129 --> 01:03:31.794
[SPEAKER_08]: There were actually, oddly, some kind of conciliatory moments in this debate too.

01:03:32.375 --> 01:03:46.035
[SPEAKER_08]: Most notably a moment when the two leaders shook hands, when Julie Etchingham was asking them whether they could shake hands and promise not to allow this kind of festering anger in politics to grow and to become any worse.

01:03:46.055 --> 01:03:50.001
[SPEAKER_08]: And there was an interesting moment when they were asked, I think we've got a clip of it here actually,

01:03:49.981 --> 01:03:54.569
[SPEAKER_08]: whether they would give each other a Christmas present and what they'd leave each other under the tree.

01:03:54.589 --> 01:03:57.073
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's have a little listen to the answers that they gave to that.

01:03:58.976 --> 01:04:02.682
[SPEAKER_02]: Leaving politics aside, gentlemen.

01:04:02.702 --> 01:04:07.890
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, leaving politics aside, what gift would you leave for Mr. Johnson under the Christmas tree?

01:04:07.991 --> 01:04:10.054
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I know Mr. Johnson likes a good read.

01:04:10.755 --> 01:04:16.765
[SPEAKER_17]: So what I would probably leave under the tree for him would be a Christmas carol by Charles Dickens.

01:04:18.263 --> 01:04:20.786
[SPEAKER_17]: And he can now understand how nasty Scrooge was.

01:04:22.228 --> 01:04:22.548
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

01:04:22.568 --> 01:04:23.149
[SPEAKER_20]: Mr. Johnson.

01:04:23.909 --> 01:04:32.199
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I think, well, I would probably leave a copy of, since you want a literary effort, a copy of my brilliant Brexit deal.

01:04:36.123 --> 01:04:40.288
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, well, in that spirit, maybe I could ask you two, what would you leave each other under the Christmas tree?

01:04:40.388 --> 01:04:41.149
[SPEAKER_08]: Dawn, let's start with you.

01:04:41.197 --> 01:04:43.903
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, I've got the perfect present for Boris Johnson.

01:04:44.665 --> 01:04:46.428
[SPEAKER_08]: You're going to leave one for Priti Patel?

01:04:46.448 --> 01:04:47.150
[SPEAKER_08]: She hasn't got a gift for you.

01:04:47.170 --> 01:04:48.834
[SPEAKER_19]: First of all, I'd like to leave Boris a present.

01:04:49.315 --> 01:04:50.878
[SPEAKER_19]: A lie detector test.

01:04:50.898 --> 01:04:52.301
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, OK. And for Priti Patel?

01:04:52.802 --> 01:04:59.577
[SPEAKER_19]: For Priti Patel, I will leave you a pretty... a lovely pair of shoes.

01:04:59.945 --> 01:05:01.968
[SPEAKER_08]: That's actually quite nice.

01:05:02.008 --> 01:05:11.401
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I will tell you, I'm an Essex MP and I have one of the world famous jam factories in my constituency, Wilkin and Sons, and I would gift Dawn some beautiful jams from Essex.

01:05:11.702 --> 01:05:14.466
[SPEAKER_08]: Well, it is an election, you've got to go and plug your constituency, haven't you?

01:05:14.486 --> 01:05:16.609
[SPEAKER_08]: Dawn Butler, Priti Patel, thank you so much for joining me.

01:05:17.070 --> 01:05:18.812
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, so that's the verdict of the politicians.

01:05:18.832 --> 01:05:22.257
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's just take another quick look at the snap poll that I tweeted earlier.

01:05:22.237 --> 01:05:23.579
[SPEAKER_08]: Remember, this isn't scientific.

01:05:23.599 --> 01:05:25.181
[SPEAKER_08]: This has gone out on social media.

01:05:25.261 --> 01:05:28.025
[SPEAKER_08]: It's liable to be manipulated by various parties.

01:05:28.045 --> 01:05:31.009
[SPEAKER_08]: 78% say Jeremy Corbyn won that debate.

01:05:31.029 --> 01:05:33.151
[SPEAKER_08]: 22% say Boris Johnson.

01:05:33.632 --> 01:05:36.876
[SPEAKER_08]: We do know that Labour is a little bit more engaged on social media.

01:05:36.896 --> 01:05:38.098
[SPEAKER_08]: So let's just take it with a pinch of salt.

01:05:38.118 --> 01:05:40.261
[SPEAKER_08]: But an interesting result there nonetheless.

01:05:40.461 --> 01:05:43.385
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, let's go for a little roam around the room, shall we?

01:05:44.226 --> 01:05:45.508
[SPEAKER_08]: Who have we got in the room?

01:05:46.149 --> 01:05:48.352
[SPEAKER_08]: So over here, we've got the Brexit party.

01:05:48.652 --> 01:05:50.134
[SPEAKER_08]: Gawain, are we allowed to speak to you tonight?

01:05:50.300 --> 01:05:52.947
[SPEAKER_06]: I've got to put that in the press office, don't I?

01:05:52.967 --> 01:05:53.830
[SPEAKER_08]: Who have you got we can speak to?

01:05:53.890 --> 01:05:55.053
[SPEAKER_08]: We've got Richard Tice over there.

01:05:55.354 --> 01:05:56.658
[SPEAKER_08]: We have a very quick word.

01:05:56.959 --> 01:06:00.268
[SPEAKER_08]: A very short word, Richard Tice, if you may, the chair of the Brexit party.

01:06:00.749 --> 01:06:02.033
[SPEAKER_05]: What did you make of that debate?

01:06:02.053 --> 01:06:05.322
[SPEAKER_05]: I thought it was pretty fiery, as you'd expect.

01:06:05.302 --> 01:06:15.325
[SPEAKER_05]: The main thing that came out of it for us, the Brexit party, was the prime minister's reaffirmation of his pledge that the transition period will definitely end in December 20.

01:06:15.746 --> 01:06:20.998
[SPEAKER_05]: Otherwise, there was all sorts of nonsense and lies portrayed by Jeremy Corbyn about privatising the NHS.

01:06:20.978 --> 01:06:22.279
[SPEAKER_05]: Everybody needs to just forget that.

01:06:22.299 --> 01:06:23.380
[SPEAKER_05]: That's utter nonsense.

01:06:23.400 --> 01:06:28.725
[SPEAKER_08]: So does the Brexit party feel even more comfortable about endorsing effectively Boris Johnson after that debate?

01:06:28.905 --> 01:06:32.228
[SPEAKER_05]: We're always going to keep holding the Conservatives to account on this key issue.

01:06:32.448 --> 01:06:33.048
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to leave.

01:06:33.288 --> 01:06:34.269
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to leave properly.

01:06:34.529 --> 01:06:35.450
[SPEAKER_05]: And we need to get on with it.

01:06:35.650 --> 01:06:41.235
[SPEAKER_05]: And the Prime Minister has reaffirmed that by us winning seats in the House of Commons in this election, we can hold them to account.

01:06:41.255 --> 01:06:42.656
[SPEAKER_08]: OK. Richard Tice, thank you very much.

01:06:43.037 --> 01:06:44.078
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's see who else is in the room.

01:06:44.158 --> 01:06:45.599
[SPEAKER_08]: We need to try and get round this way, don't we?

01:06:45.619 --> 01:06:48.161
[SPEAKER_08]: If we just come over here, round the corner.

01:06:48.181 --> 01:06:50.563
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, I can smell some food, actually, in here.

01:06:51.100 --> 01:06:51.781
[SPEAKER_08]: What is in here?

01:06:51.801 --> 01:06:54.585
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, that looks really good, actually.

01:06:55.687 --> 01:06:57.229
[SPEAKER_08]: Looks like chili, is it?

01:06:58.511 --> 01:06:58.811
[SPEAKER_08]: Chili.

01:06:59.011 --> 01:07:00.293
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, okay, I'll get some of that later.

01:07:01.575 --> 01:07:05.381
[SPEAKER_08]: And then just over here, we have our podcast team.

01:07:05.461 --> 01:07:06.302
[SPEAKER_08]: Hello, good evening.

01:07:06.342 --> 01:07:10.528
[SPEAKER_08]: Our Calling Peston podcast team, who are preparing for a special edition tonight, aren't you?

01:07:11.049 --> 01:07:14.193
[SPEAKER_08]: So guys, what's on the podcast tonight, and what did you make of the debate you actually had?

01:07:14.213 --> 01:07:19.881
[SPEAKER_15]: So we're gonna go through all the best bits from tonight's debate, and then we're gonna be looking at, we're talking to spinners on both sides.

01:07:19.901 --> 01:07:21.023
[SPEAKER_15]: What was your favorite bit?

01:07:21.003 --> 01:07:21.764
[SPEAKER_15]: My favourite bit?

01:07:21.804 --> 01:07:26.852
[SPEAKER_15]: I thought fascinating that Jeremy Corbyn didn't answer that question on which way he's going to be voting if there's another Brexit referendum.

01:07:26.872 --> 01:07:31.239
[SPEAKER_15]: I think that's going to be the key takeaway from the Tories, but we'll be speaking to spinners from both sides to get their reaction.

01:07:31.259 --> 01:07:32.000
[SPEAKER_07]: Dan, what did you make of it?

01:07:32.160 --> 01:07:35.746
[SPEAKER_07]: I thought it was really interesting, the fact that the audience was so animated.

01:07:35.846 --> 01:07:37.789
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think we've ever seen an audience that animated.

01:07:37.809 --> 01:07:39.872
[SPEAKER_07]: And quite angry in front of, you know, cynical.

01:07:39.852 --> 01:07:43.596
[SPEAKER_07]: It's genuinely, I think, the sign of the times, Paul, that we had a debate on television like that.

01:07:43.837 --> 01:07:45.558
[SPEAKER_07]: Previous debates have not had an audience like that.

01:07:46.039 --> 01:07:48.862
[SPEAKER_07]: Whooping, clapping, almost booing people's reactions.

01:07:49.263 --> 01:07:54.469
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's a sign of the times that politics is so divided and people... And that gloss of politicians has kind of gone.

01:07:54.849 --> 01:07:57.192
[SPEAKER_07]: People feel like they can shout at them, boo at them, clap at them whenever they want now.

01:07:57.212 --> 01:07:58.413
[SPEAKER_08]: Yeah, they're sort of fair game, aren't they?

01:07:58.433 --> 01:07:59.394
[SPEAKER_08]: Very much so, yeah.

01:07:59.414 --> 01:08:01.436
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, guys, well, good luck with the podcast this evening.

01:08:01.757 --> 01:08:02.398
[SPEAKER_08]: See you, Paul.

01:08:02.418 --> 01:08:03.158
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll see you later.

01:08:03.178 --> 01:08:03.519
[SPEAKER_08]: Hello, Lewis.

01:08:04.380 --> 01:08:06.062
[SPEAKER_08]: Right, let's try and get back now.

01:08:06.262 --> 01:08:06.763
[SPEAKER_08]: Can we do it?

01:08:06.983 --> 01:08:07.924
[SPEAKER_08]: Can we squeeze around this way?

01:08:08.124 --> 01:08:08.965
[SPEAKER_08]: Maybe if we go...

01:08:08.945 --> 01:08:10.431
[SPEAKER_08]: Oh, this is going to be a dead end this way.

01:08:10.973 --> 01:08:11.716
[SPEAKER_08]: That's a bad idea.

01:08:11.756 --> 01:08:13.101
[SPEAKER_08]: Robert.

01:08:13.161 --> 01:08:16.795
[SPEAKER_10]: We're going to the same place as you, Robert.

01:08:17.669 --> 01:08:18.590
[SPEAKER_08]: He's not listening to me.

01:08:18.610 --> 01:08:19.371
[SPEAKER_08]: Robert Peston, hello.

01:08:19.552 --> 01:08:21.915
[SPEAKER_08]: You're coming with me, you're live on ITV, don't forget that, don't forget.

01:08:22.796 --> 01:08:23.678
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm chasing you down.

01:08:24.118 --> 01:08:26.582
[SPEAKER_08]: Come on, come over to the live spot, come over to this camera here.

01:08:27.002 --> 01:08:29.666
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's have one final chat with you, Robert Peston, our fiscal editor, of course.

01:08:29.907 --> 01:08:32.751
[SPEAKER_08]: If you come here, just so we can get a good shot of you.

01:08:32.771 --> 01:08:36.155
[SPEAKER_08]: Okay, do you think that debate changed anything in this election, Robert?

01:08:36.877 --> 01:08:37.497
[SPEAKER_10]: Probably not.

01:08:38.539 --> 01:08:42.124
[SPEAKER_10]: I actually thought both leaders performed

01:08:42.104 --> 01:08:44.731
[SPEAKER_10]: actually as well as their teams could have hoped.

01:08:44.771 --> 01:08:48.101
[SPEAKER_10]: There were no significant fluffs.

01:08:48.602 --> 01:08:57.126
[SPEAKER_10]: As I'm sure you've been saying to all our guests, or talking about with all our guests,

01:08:57.106 --> 01:09:05.774
[SPEAKER_10]: Boris Johnson was at time monotonously consistent about his get Brexit done line.

01:09:05.794 --> 01:09:13.100
[SPEAKER_10]: He used every possible question, even some, which did not seem particularly relevant to the Brexit question.

01:09:13.821 --> 01:09:21.068
[SPEAKER_10]: He used every possible question to get back to the fact that he claims that he has a simple deal that will get through Parliament.

01:09:21.088 --> 01:09:27.113
[SPEAKER_10]: I was slightly surprised, for example, though, that Jeremy Corbyn didn't challenge him about how he was going to get his trade deal done by the end of 2020.

01:09:27.093 --> 01:09:30.502
[SPEAKER_10]: which some would say is a weakness of Johnson.

01:09:30.522 --> 01:09:36.278
[SPEAKER_08]: He did pull out that document at one point about the NHS being on the table, which for Labour has actually been quite an effective argument.

01:09:36.478 --> 01:09:41.271
[SPEAKER_10]: It has been, but Johnson was absolutely categoric.

01:09:41.504 --> 01:09:46.352
[SPEAKER_10]: that he will not allow privatization of the NHS as a result of a trade deal.

01:09:46.372 --> 01:09:58.110
[SPEAKER_10]: And he went as far as he could to dismiss the idea that American drug companies will be given the kind of access to the NHS which would drive up drug prices.

01:09:59.212 --> 01:10:04.761
[SPEAKER_10]: But that is, in a way, Johnson's weakest position.

01:10:04.741 --> 01:10:16.266
[SPEAKER_10]: The other part of it, though, that I thought was really interesting, and obviously it's not been at the heart of the general election, but they were asked about whether the monarchy was fit for purpose.

01:10:16.647 --> 01:10:21.838
[SPEAKER_10]: And what was really interesting was that Jeremy Corbyn said room for improvement.

01:10:21.818 --> 01:10:24.184
[SPEAKER_10]: And actually got some applause in the room.

01:10:24.204 --> 01:10:28.194
[SPEAKER_08]: And if he'd said that before the Prince Andrew episode, he might not have got the same applause.

01:10:28.214 --> 01:10:28.655
[SPEAKER_10]: Exactly.

01:10:28.916 --> 01:10:35.252
[SPEAKER_10]: And it was very interesting that when Boris Johnson said, it's beyond reproach, you could hear a pin drop.

01:10:35.272 --> 01:10:38.781
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, there's no question that in that audience,

01:10:38.761 --> 01:10:40.645
[SPEAKER_10]: Corbyn had the better of that.

01:10:41.486 --> 01:10:47.699
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm not so sure that in the country at large, Corbyn's position on the monarchy will be quite so popular.

01:10:47.779 --> 01:10:53.831
[SPEAKER_10]: Obviously, Prince Andrew has changed the nature of the debate, that controversial interview.

01:10:54.092 --> 01:10:57.799
[SPEAKER_10]: But I still think, you know, the majority of British people

01:10:58.117 --> 01:10:59.598
[SPEAKER_10]: broadly love the Queen.

01:10:59.659 --> 01:11:11.410
[SPEAKER_10]: And so I don't really know how that's going to play, whether in the country at large, it'll play quite the same way as it played in that hall.

01:11:11.630 --> 01:11:19.718
[SPEAKER_10]: But as I say, the key thing, it seems to me, is that neither leader made what I regard as a significant error.

01:11:20.859 --> 01:11:23.762
[SPEAKER_10]: Both actually were quite good on their stronger points.

01:11:24.783 --> 01:11:26.605
[SPEAKER_10]: Johnson on.

01:11:26.585 --> 01:11:33.494
[SPEAKER_10]: getting his deal done, and Corbyn on public services, particularly the NHS.

01:11:33.514 --> 01:11:34.715
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, yeah.

01:11:34.735 --> 01:11:38.019
[SPEAKER_10]: So I guess they will both come out of it feeling sort of OK.

01:11:38.200 --> 01:11:40.683
[SPEAKER_10]: Think it's sort of a score draw for you?

01:11:40.703 --> 01:11:47.712
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, probably a sort of score-ish kind of draw, and we await the manifestos, and maybe that will change the momentum.

01:11:47.852 --> 01:11:48.873
[SPEAKER_08]: All right, Robert, thanks so much.

01:11:48.933 --> 01:11:50.656
[SPEAKER_08]: You've got to go off and do the podcast now, I think.

01:11:50.676 --> 01:11:51.336
[SPEAKER_08]: I think I probably have.

01:11:51.356 --> 01:11:52.097
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks for your time.

01:11:52.117 --> 01:11:52.558
[SPEAKER_08]: See you soon.

01:11:52.578 --> 01:11:53.419
[SPEAKER_08]: See you in a bit.

01:11:53.399 --> 01:11:54.280
[SPEAKER_08]: OK, right.

01:11:54.641 --> 01:12:00.751
[SPEAKER_08]: Let's take a look at your snap voting on Twitter now, just one more time before we finish for this evening.

01:12:01.292 --> 01:12:04.337
[SPEAKER_08]: And Jeremy Corbyn, as I said to you earlier, finished up on 78%.

01:12:04.517 --> 01:12:06.520
[SPEAKER_08]: Boris Johnson at 22%.

01:12:06.600 --> 01:12:09.004
[SPEAKER_08]: Just remember that poll is not scientific.

01:12:09.024 --> 01:12:13.111
[SPEAKER_08]: But almost 30,000 votes were cast, so quite a big sample.

01:12:13.151 --> 01:12:16.757
[SPEAKER_08]: But again, it can be skewed by various tactics on social media.

01:12:16.737 --> 01:12:19.861
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is it now here from the ITV debate Unspun.

01:12:20.221 --> 01:12:31.615
[SPEAKER_08]: Coming up at 10pm, party leaders from the Liberal Democrats, the SNP, the Brexit Party and the Green Party will be responding to the debate and setting out their own policies in the ITV election interviews.

01:12:31.655 --> 01:12:36.821
[SPEAKER_08]: You can watch that on ITV or you can stay here on itv.com slash news, Facebook, Twitter and YouTube.

01:12:36.841 --> 01:12:39.184
[SPEAKER_08]: But from all of us here in Salford, goodnight.

